Name: Ambidexter Institute (Taylor House)
Narrative:
Also known as the Judge John Wycliffe Taylor House, 
this remarkable survivor was built in 1857, at a time when Abraham Lincoln was still living in Springfield. Ten years after construction the house was converted to the Ulrich Home for Fallen Women. From 1901 to 1908 it served at the Ambidexter Industrial and Normal Institute for African American Children, modeled on Booker T. Washington's Tuskegee Institute. The house has survived multiple threats. According to the Landmarks Illinois website, “The Springfield Race Riots of 1909, which sparked the formation of the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People (NAACP), saw the Illinois National Guard protect the Ambidexter Institute from nearby rioters.” It is often described as one of the three most important Black history sites in Springfield. The Springfield Project/Black Chamber of Commerce has taken over management of the site and has received city funding for initial foundation work, which is underway. A community heritage and education center are envisioned.

Name: Arcadia Hall/Desert Scene Elks Lodge
Narrative: The Jackson Five (Jackie, Tito, Germaine, Marlon and Michael) spent summers in Winslow in the late 1960s with their grandfather, Samuel Jackson, and performed in this Black Elks lodge just off of Route 66. They practiced at their grandfather’s home at 317 Snyder Avenue and performed several times in this lodge.

Name: Castle Car Wash
Narrative: Opened the year before Route 66 was designated a federal highway in 1926, this stone-veneered structure functioned as a service station for travelers and area residents for more than 40 years. It then became a carwash and later an auto storage lot. It is viewed as a distinctive historic Route 66 landmark by the surrounding North Lawndale community, which today is predominantly African American. The North Lawndale Historical and Cultural Society would like to acquire the building to create a heritage and community center.

Name: Central Park Theater
Narrative: Built in 1917 and designed by Rapp & Rapp, the Central Park Theater in North Lawndale has been described as Chicago’s first movie palace. In its early days the theater served the predominantly Jewish population of North Lawndale. The area became majority Black in the 1950s. In addition to movies, notable performers have included Benny Goodman and The Jackson 5. The theater closed in 1971 and the House of Prayer Church of God has been stewarding it since. Repair needs are significant, and the church is seeking a preservation-minded development partner to create a community performance and gathering space. The project is a high priority for the North Lawndale Historical and Cultural Society.

Name: Greenwood Historic District
Narrative: Once known as Tulsa’s Black Wall Street, this area suffered a horrific race massacre in 1921 where a significant portion of the neighborhood was burned or destroyed. The facades of buildings along Greenwood Avenue survive, though the buildings behind them are complete new builds.

Name: Renovating Greenwood Rising's Walking Tour Application
Joplin Union Depot
Narrative: Built in 1911, the Joplin Union Depot is adjacent to the original alignment of Route 66 that is now Langston Hughes-Broadway (Hughes grew up in Joplin). Once a major commercial corridor, this area (known as East Town) went into decline as the result of urban renewal and discriminatory housing policies. Many area residents today feel their history is overshadowed. Rehabilitation of the depot would bring new attention and activity to the area, complementing and supporting other community-led revitalization efforts farther east into the residential parts of the neighborhood. Vacant since 1969, the Union Depot is owned by the Missouri Department of Natural Resources (SHPO), which acquired the property in 1998 when they had to foreclose on a previous owner who had received a grant through their state Historic Preservation Revolving Fund. The current vision for reuse of the Depot is a mix of local retail and restaurants.

Name: Liberty Theater
Narrative: During segregation, the balcony of the Liberty was the only place African Americans and Latinos could go to watch a movie in Amarillo. It is close to Route 66.

Name: Majestic Theater
Narrative:
Built in 1928, this once grand theater in downtown East St. Louis featured Spanish Revival architectural motifs and was the first theater in the area to have air conditioning. The Majestic closed in 1960 and has sat vacant and deteriorating, along with numerous 
other nearby historic structures, ever since. Once a thriving industrial center, East St. Louis was the site of a horrific race riot in 1917. Industrial decline, combined with decades of racist policies and practices, have made it one of the poorest cities in the nation.

Name: Miles Davis House
Narrative: Former home of the late Miles Dewey Davis II, a significant jazz trumpeter and important 20th century musician. The building currently houses the House of Miles Leadership to “nurture, empower and embrace the talents of upcoming generations by reclaiming, restoring and revitalizing our values, identity and Cool.” 2026 would have been Miles Davis’ 100th birthday.

Name: Mr. Powdrell’s Barbeque House
Narrative: The Powdrell family moved to Albuquerque from Louisiana in 1958. Pete Powdrell opened his first restaurant in the North Valley in 1962, using a barbeque recipe from his great-grandfather Isaac Britt.

Name: Murdoch Community Center
Narrative: This site is home to Flagstaff’s Southside Community Association (SCA) and serves as a multi-cultural community center reflecting the different cultures of the racially diverse Southside.

Name: Quinn Chapel
Narrative:
Quinn Chapel is one of the few remaining historic structures in the tiny town of Brooklyn, Illinois, which began in the 1820s as a settlement of African Americans escaping slavery. It is one of two verified Underground Railroad sites in the East St. Louis area. In 1873 Brooklyn became the nation’s first community to be incorporated by African Americans. 
The town is located just across the Mississippi River from St. Louis and near one of the original alignments of Route 66. Today Brooklyn is home to just over 700 residents and 12 churches, along with a concentration of adult entertainment venues. A local historical society is leading archeological, preservation, and education efforts, including restoration of the Chapel.

Name: Sara Lou Cafe
Narrative:
The Sara Lou Cafe (1906) is one of the handful of Green Book sites that remains standing in Missouri. Located just a few blocks off one of primary the Route 66 alignments through the Greater Ville Neighborhood in St. Louis, the café served both Black travelers and 
area residents. Though vacant and in very poor condition, the café is on a corner with three other intact, two-story commercial buildings in an area where residential blocks retain significant historic fabric. As described on the Missouri Preservation website, “The Ville Neighborhood is representative of the resilience of African Americans in St. Louis to thrive and prosper in an age that was marked by racism and exclusion.” Northside Community Housing, Inc. has an option on the property, which is owned by the St. Louis Land Reutilization Authority (land bank). A mixed-use rehabilitation project is envisioned.

Name: South Town Theater
Narrative: The Empress Theater opened in 1915 and was remodeled and renamed the South Town Theater in 1937. It was a key attraction in the South Town area, which is predominately African American, for several decades. The property has been acquired by the Springfield Project/Black Chamber of Commerce, which is planning a phased rehabilitation of several historic properties on the block, including a small corner commercial building and furniture store, as well as the theater. A performing arts space for K-12 students and the area community is envisioned.

Name: Herring Hotel
Narrative: Big bands used to play in the ballroom on the mezzanine level including Duke Ellington and others.

Name: Magnolia Gas Station
Narrative: In the economically depressed TX Panhandle, though Vega may be less economically depressed than other communities with 8% of residents living in poverty in 2019.

Name: Magnolia Gas Station
Narrative: Vega, Texas was very photogenic when I visited the only time in 2019. I was about to head into a storm but managed to capture lots of pictures like this one just in time. Vega had lots of history, from the placement of the Ten Commandments to the end of Texas Route 66 - one would have to jump onto I-40 to enter Adrian and eventually head into New Mexico.

Name: Paradise Motel
Narrative: Tucumcari is in an economically distressed part of New Mexico. The loss of Route 66 motels in recent months has been a particular challenge in New Mexico (particularly in Gallup), as well as issues with vandalism and spray painting.

Name: Paradise Motel - Tucumcari, NM
Status_Note: Building is still standing but is in rough condition. Has suffered multiple fires in 2018 according to Route 66 News. Old signs were recently removed.

Name: Phillips 66 Station
Narrative: As of 2019, 24.2% of the residents of McLean in the Texas panhandle were living in poverty making this an economically distressed part of Route 66. This gas station was built and leased to Phillips in 1929. It was the first Phillips 66 station in the state of Texas, and it was the first restored station on Old Route 66.

Name: Roark’s Hardware
Narrative:
In the economically depressed TX Panhandle, though Vega may be less economically depressed than other communities with 8% of residents living in poverty in 2019. Roark’s was the oldest operating hardware store on Route 66, dating back to 1929 in the building shown above. There is a museum around the corner (Milburn Price & Culture Museum) on 
Coke Street that was original the Western Lumber Store, and Roark’s history is connected to that.

Name: Super Service Station
Narrative: 34.5% of the population of Alanreed, Texas is living below the poverty line making this one of Route 66’s economically distressed communities. This 1930 Kaiser 66 station was one of the first double gas stations with pumps on both sides.

Name: Asian District (Little Saigon)
Narrative: Oklahoma’s largest population of Asian immigrants can be found in Oklahoma City’s Asian District. The district began to form in 1975 when Vietnamese refugees can to OKC after the fall of Saigon.

Name: Fort Reno Cemetery
Narrative: The Fort Reno cemetery includes graves of 62 German and Italian prisoners of war who were brought to Oklahoma during World War II. As many as 20,000 German POWs came to Oklahoma during WWII and were held at different remote camps.

Name: Hawthorne Works Water Tower and Fire House
Narrative: Western Electric’s Hawthorne Works produced an array of electrical products, primarily for the Bell system as well as the U.S. government (especially during WWII). In its heyday, Western Electric’s Hawthorne Works employed over 40,000 workers in a vast complex of more than 2.5 million square feet that included 11 employee cafeterias and its own hospital and fire department. Many of the employees were recent Czech and Polish immigrants, who settled in the towns of Cicero and Berwyn, just across the border from the city of Chicago. The facility closed in 1986 and by 1994 all buildings except the cable building and the water tower had been demolished to make way for a collection of big box retail outlets.

Name: Hawthorne Works Water Tower and Fire House
Narrative:
Western Electric’s Hawthorne Works produced an array of electrical products, primarily for the Bell system as well as the U.S. government (especially during WWII). In its heyday, Western Electric’s Hawthorne Works employed over 40,000 workers in a vast complex of more than 2.5 million square feet that included 11 employee cafeterias and its own 
hospital and fire department. Many of the employees were recent Czech and Polish immigrants, who settled in the towns of Cicero and Berwyn, just across the border from the city of Chicago. The facility closed in 1986 and by 1994 all buildings except the cable building and the water tower had been demolished to make way for a collection of big box retail outlets.

Name: Madison/J Flats boarding houses
Narrative:
Built in 1914, these two structures in East Hollywood are rare examples of boarding houses that provided homes for Japanese immigrants seeking affordable and safe housing in the early 20th century and again after World War II, when Japanese Americans 
returned from internment camps. Still home to several single Japanese men, these boarding houses were recently purchased by a new owner. The LA Conservancy fought successfully to landmark the structures, but there are still concerns that the seven long-time residents may be forced out by increasing rents.

Name: The Jade Restaurant
Narrative: Restaurant founded by Charlie Hing Lum, a prominent member of Kingman’s long-standing Chinese community. Lum immigrated to the US in 1912 from Canton at the age of ten. After various roles with restaurants in San Francisco and elsewhere, Charlie returned to Kingman in 1951 to open a Chinese restaurant (one of the first in NW Arizona). Lum was the first Chinese member of the Kingman Elks Lodge, the Rotary Club, and an honorary member of the Lions. He supported many local sports teams and events. He expanded his real estate holding in Kingman with a coin operated laundromat in 1964 and a ten unit “Lum’s Apartments.” The Jade was sold to Tommy Choy in 1965 who gave it a Polynesian makeover with flaming torches and a Bora-Bora room.

Name: Jade Restaurant 1
Status_Note: Building is still standing but abandoned according to Never Quite Lost.

Name: Jade Restaurant 2
Status_Note: Building still standing but vacant according to Never Quite Lost.

Name: Little Bosnia
Narrative:
Route 66 in St. Louis passes through several ethnically diverse communities. In the 19th century German immigrants settled in the Bevo Mill neighborhood, named after a restaurant and beer hall opened by August Busch in 1917. The neighborhood features a 
windmill that was a landmark for travelers along Route 66. In the 1990s the neighborhood became a center for Bosnian refugees escaping conflict in the former Yugoslavia. They were drawn to the area by the affordable housing stock and opportunity to start small businesses, often in older commercial buildings on and near Route 66. Today the area is a thriving district of small businesses and restaurants, including many that serve goulash, tarhana, and other Balkan fare. The area continues to serve as an entry point for refugees, including recent arrivals from Afghanistan.

Name: Town of Rosati
Narrative:
Originally known as Knobview, the name of this small settlement along Route 66 in central Missouri was changed to Rosati in 1931 at the urging of Italian immigrants who settled in the region in the 1890s. News of the name change reached Mussolini’s fascist 
regime in Italy, which touted the story in magazines and newspapers. The Italian immigrants introduced grapes to the area and built a thriving wine and grape juice industry. Some legacy vineyards, wineries, and fruit stands are still active. Two Route 66 era gas stations have disappeared, but a handful of historic structures remain.

Name: Yukon’s Best Flour Mills
Narrative:
The founders of Yukon’s Best Flour Bill emigrated to the U.S. from Czechoslovakia in the late 1800s. Brothers John and Frank Kroutil purchased the Yukon Mill and Grain Company in 1902 and ran the business until the 1950s. The brothers also opened the Yukon National Park, John served as president of the Yukon Electric Company and was a co-founder of the Progress Brewing Company, one of only three post prohibition brewing licenses issued in Oklahoma. John was also the vice president of the National Association of Roosevelt Czechoslovakian Clubs of America and was inducted into the Oklahoma Hall of Fame in 1933. Yukon’s Czechoslovakian heritage is celebrated every year at the Czech 
Festival Yukon OK which features Czech festivities, food, parade, dances and kolaches.

Name: Angel & Vilma Delgadillo’s Original Route 66 Gift Shop
Narrative:
Angel Delgadillo was born on Route 66 in 1927, and grew up to be a barber like his father, studying in Pasadena and apprenticing in Williams, AZ (both on Route 66). In 
1972, he moved his barber shop to be on a new alignment of Route 66. When I-40 opened two miles south of Seligman in 1978, Angel led the effort to have the state of Arizona make Route 66 a historic highway. In 1987, he helped found the Historic Route 66 Association of Arizona, the first statewide Route 66 association. Shortly thereafter the state of Arizona did designate Route 66 as a historic highway. Angel and his wife Vilma have continued to operate a gift shop on Route 66, and Angel (known as the “Guardian Angel” of Route 66) just retired as a barber in July 2022 at the age of 95 after working for 75 years in the barber trade. Shortly after retiring, Delgadillo was inducted into the Arizona Tourism Hall of Fame.

Name: Angel & Vilma Delgadillo's Original Route 66 Gift Shop
Historic Angel's Barber Shop Museum
Narrative: July 2013, because Angel has done so much for the Route 66 community, we thought of bringing him a gift, we e-mailed his daughter to find out wich shoesize Angel has, after that we bought some Dutch wooden shoes, custom painted them in an Americana/Seligman theme, gladly when we arrived in Seligman Angel was there to try them on, he really liked them, they keep them safe in a showcase in the Barbershop

Name: barrio neighborhood
Narrative: Mexican workers came to this neighborhood starting in 1889 to work for the Santa Fe Railroad. The neighborhood was built to house railroad workers and their families.

Name: Mitla Cafe
Narrative:
Lucia Rodriguez opened the Mitla Café in 1937 as a lunch counter serving travelers on Route 66. The café quickly became popular with local residents, including immigrants from Mexico who were restricted to living in the surrounding neighborhood of west San Bernadino. The café was frequented by Cesar Chavez and other civil rights leaders and 
continues to serve as a family-owned community gathering place. Another regular was Glen Bell, who owned a hot dog and hamburger stand across the street and copied recipes from the Mitla Café to use in a new restaurant he opened in Downey, California in 1962, which eventually grew to become the Taco Bell fast food chain. The story of Lucia Rodriguez is featured in Women of the Mother Road documentary.

Name: Whiting Brothers Station #72
Narrative: Operated by Whiting Brothers from 1954-1985 when the station was purchased by long-time employee Sal Lucero. Lucero has operated this gas station on Route 66 ever since. While gas is no longer sold at the station, it’s still a place to get your tires fixed. Whiting Brothers started in 1926 and established several gas stations and motels along Route 66. It is the only operating Whiting Brothers station with the original signs.

Name: The Whiting Brothers Service Station
Narrative: The Whiting Brothers Service Station in Moriarty is the last operating station under this iconic brand. Sal Lucero had worked at the station for many years before purchasing it in the 1980s. You can't get gas anymore, but you can get tires, a battery, and an unforgettable conversation.

Name: The Last Whiting Brothers
Narrative: The Last Whiting Bros., oil on linen, 24 x 36 © 2024While driving Route 66 as a kid in the back of the family station wagon, reading billboards was a favorite pastime. The ubiquitous big yellow Whiting Bros. signs proclaiming "Whiting Bros - Gas for Less - 50 miles" were a way to know we were approaching a town. Dad would often stop in for a fill-up and "Free Ice" to replenish the aluminum cooler where Mom's sandwiches were awaiting a roadside picnic. Once a family-owned chain of 100 gas stations and motels from Texas to California, Whiting Bros. went the way of many independent businesses when I- 40 bypassed Route 66. This station, in Moriarty, NM, was the last survivor. It was sold to a longtime employee in 1985 and is still operating as The Sal and Inez Service Station. The Last of the iconic Whiting Bros. signs was restored in 2014 with a matching grant from the National Park Service Route 66 Corridor Preservation Program.

Name: NW 39th Street District
Narrative: OKC’s gay community also known as “The Strip”

Name: Route 66 Augmented Reality History Experience on 39th Street
Donnay Building
Narrative: The Donnay Building is home to several longtime legacy businesses in OKC including the HiLo Club and the Classen Grill, as well as beloved former businesses such as the Patio Grill Restaurant (which opened in 1954 and operated for 3 decades) and Charlie’s Records. The HiLo Club, which opened in 1956 as a private live music bar, was one of the city’s leading LGBT bars during the 1980s as well as being one of the oldest gay bars in the region, closed at the end of March 2022.

Name: Acoma Pueblo/Sky City
Narrative: Known as the oldest continuously inhabited community in North America (established 1150 A.D.) and located at the top of a 367-foot sandstone bluff. Home to a federally recognized Native American Tribe.

Name: Baxter Springs Route 66 Visitor Center
Narrative:
Baxter Springs is the largest of three small communities located along the 14 miles of Route 66 that pass through Kansas. A historic gas station just a block off the highway has been converted to a Route 66 visitor center. In addition to information on the era of Route 66 travel, the director of the Baxter Springs Heritage Center and Museum is seeking to 
add interpretation at the center related to the region’s Native American heritage. She believes that the Native American story of Route 66 is under-told and poorly understood. For example, tribes including the Osage and Cherokee were forced into “Neutral Lands” in southeast Kansas until they were later relocated to Oklahoma. The proposed exhibit and information center would introduce visitors to tribal history and point them to tribal cultural centers in Kansas and Oklahoma.

Name: Cahokia Mounds
Narrative: Cahokia Mounds includes more than 70 mounds built by the ancient Mississippians approximately 1,000 years ago. The region was home to as many as 100,000 people at its peak. Eleven Native American tribes trace their ancestry to the Mississippians, and all are supportive of legislation introduced by Rep. Mike Bost (R) Sen. Dick Durbin (D) to create the “Cahokia Mounds and Mississippian Culture National Historic Park” (HR 2642/SB 1211). Currently the Cahokia Mounds are managed as an Illinois state park. The proposed national park would increase awareness and bring additional resources and protections for the Cahokia Mounds and other nearby mounds in Illinois, along with the Sugarloaf Mound in St. Louis, Missouri which the Osage Nation has acquired for preservation. All are near Route 66.

Name: El Pueblo Motel
Narrative: Philip Johnston built the El Pueblo Motel in 1936. It is best known because Johnston came up with the idea to have the military enlist Navajos as Code Talkers in WWII, with communications in the Navajo language intended to foil Japanese attempts to listen to American military communications. Members of the Navajo nation recruited to take part in this effort would often stay at the El Pueblo Motel before being shipped out to join the Marines as Code Talkers.

Name: Laguna Pueblo
Narrative: The ancestors of this pueblo many have occupied the Laguna homelands since at least 1300 A.D. Laguna Pueblo has size villages (Encinal, Laguna, Mesita, Paguate, Paraje and Seama), and each has its own feast day as well as a joint celebration on September 19th when native arts and crafts are available. Travelers can also visit the St. Joseph/San Jose Mission church. Laguna Pueblo is a federally recognized tribe, and tribal members speak English and Keresan.

Name: Navajo Ordnance Depot
Narrative: Native Americans helped build Camp Navajo, and many helped operate the depot during the war, with most living in one of two “Indian Villages.” A school was established for the children, and traders from the Navajo reservation opened the Richardson’s Trading Post in 1943. “Navajos, Hopis, Hispanics, Blacks, women and POWs worked side by side, and worked effectively. Through the war, 1.3 million tons of munitions were moved with astonishing efficiency.” (see link). The village was in use until 1971 when the depot was placed on reserve status.

Name: Ostermann Service Station
Narrative: The c.1929 Osterman Service Station, which is located on the Hualapai Indian reservation, was listed on the NRHP in 2009 for its association with auto tourism along Route 66. The Hualapai want to rehabilitate the gas station as a visitor and interpretive center for Route 66 and Grand Canyon travelers, and also explore opportunities for this site to generate income for the tribe.

Name: Roof Repair and Stabilization of Osterman Gas Station
Peach Springs Trading Post
Narrative:
Peach Springs is within the traditional territory of the Hualapai people. E.H. Carpenter bought a trading post in 1917, and in 1926 the National Old Trails Road became part of Route 66. The 1928 Peach Tree Trading Post was built in the Pueblo Revival style and had 
stone walls, stepped parapets, vigas (exposed beams) and massive chimneys. The Hualapai could swap traditional craft items for food, cloth, medicine and other processed goods and the trading post sold crafts to Route 66 tourists. The Hualapai Tribe acquired the Peach Springs Trading Post around 1950, using it as a post office and store until 1965. In the 1970s the building became office space for Job Corps. Currently the building is used as the offices for the Hualapai Tribe Forestry, Wildlife Conservation, and Game and Fish.

Name: Peach Springs, AZ - Trading Post
Status_Note: Building is still used used as offices for the Hualapai Tribal Forestry, Wildlife Conservation, and Game and Fish.

Name: Truxton Canyon Training School
Narrative: A 1903 Indian school whose students were primarily Hualapai, but also Apache, Havasupai, Hopi, Navajo, Tohono O’odham (Papago), Pima and Yavapai in the early 20th century. The school closed in 1937. Like other schools, the goal was to provide a Euroamerican education to assimilate Indian children in environments completely different from their own.

Name: Twin Arrows Trading Post
Narrative:
This iconic Route 66 site, which opened c. 1946, was owned and operated by William and Jean Troxell as the Twin Arrows Trading Post from 1954 to 1984, had a strong relationship with Native Traders and especially the Hopi. The site includes one of the few original 
Valentine diners still standing in its original location. While the land is owned by the State of Arizona Land Department, the buildings were given to the Hopi Tribe who own other land in the area.

Name: Twin Arrows Trading Post Ruins - Historic Route 66
Narrative: 'It is better to fill your head with useless knowledge than no knowledge at all.' - Jim Hinckley. The Twin Arrows marked the remains of the truck stop opened sometime around 1950. I was able to capture this image before vandals eventually brought them down.

Name: Twin Arrows
Narrative: Normally I'm not a fan of graffiti, but this painting I saw on the one remaining standing arrow at the Twin Arrows ghost town on Route 66 in Arizona caught my eye when I was passing through in November of 2022.  The owners who took over this trading post in the 1950s and renamed it "Twin Arrows" made these out of telephone poles to catch the attention of travelers. It's worth a stop as you are passing through Twin Arrows.  It is on the other side of the Interstate from the much newer Navajo Twin Arrows Casino.

Name: Twin arrows
Narrative: Summer of 2023, I was awarded a National Endowment for the Humanities scholarship to study Racialized Spaces on Route 66 at Northern Arizona University in Flagstaff, Arizona.  I have taught Route 66 and American Roadside Architecture at Bucks County Community College in Newtown, Pennsylvania for three semesters.  That may have been my credential for studying Route 66.  On July 12, 2023, our class had a field trip to look at how Native Culture was portrayed during Route 66 and how is it today?  We stopped to see the ruins of the Twin Arrows trading post and we were asked to juxtapose our photos with images of the Twin Arrows Casino nearby.

Name: Blue Spruce Lodge
Narrative: TBD

Name: Casa Grande Hotel
Narrative: TBD

Name: Glancy Motel
Narrative: TBD

Name: Glancy Motor Hotel
Status_Note: Building has been demolished according to oklahomaroute66.com.

Name: The Glancy Motel
Narrative: I took this photo of the Glancy Motel as I was driving through Clinton, Oklahoma back in 2009. So many great details on this 1950 Route 66 treasure! Love the vintage motel sign, the Googie-style upswept roof, the tiled walls and the cool second floor railings. Visited the site again in November of 2023 and was so glad to see that it was still there?even the original pool. However, it was still vacant which always worries me. Sadly, I learned the motel was torn down just a few days after my visit. It?s a real shame to lose a special place like the Glancy.

Name: Jarrot Mansion
Narrative: Completed in 1810 and the earliest standing masonry structure in Illinois, the Jarrot Mansion was built by a French fur trader, judge, and developer in what became the town of Cahokia. Located just a few blocks from Route 66, the Mansion is now a state historic site that has struggled to attract visitation from local residents, who have become increasingly African American in recent decades. A friends group is interested in adding interpretation that includes the important indigenous history and stories connected to people of color, including those who were enslaved as well as free.

Name: Santa Fe Depot
Narrative: TBD

Name: Santa Monica Boulevard
Narrative: Route 66 follows Santa Monica Boulevard through much of west Los Angeles. Lined with structures from numerous eras, this is one of the most culturally diverse and architecturally rich stretches of Route 66. It is also a place of regular conflict and controversy over competing goals of historic preservation, development, and housing.

Name: Tower Station and U Drop Inn
Narrative: TBD

Name: U-Drop Inn Cafe
Image_Cr: Carol M. Highsmith, Library of Congress

Name: Conoco Tower Station & U-Drop Inn Cafe
Narrative: Exploring Disney Movie "Cars" Route 66 roots. 2017 and 2019 road trips along Route 66 with our kids led to quirky stops, state parks, national parks, monuments, and historic downtowns. But the Conoco Tower Station & U-Drop Inn Cafe in Shamrock, TX is the image that brings those trips memories flooding back. The neon pop at night is unforgettable.

Name: Desert Training Center
Narrative:
A remarkable, yet brief chapter in history played out along some of the most desolate sections of Route 66 as it crosses the desert Southwest. Between 1941 and 1944, more than one million soldiers received training and participated in battle simulations at the 
Desert Training Center (DTC) in preparation for combat in the North African Campaign. The training center included a series of temporary camps set up in the sparsely inhabited Mojave Desert of southern California, as well as the Sonoran Desert in western Arizona. Several of these camps are close the Route 66 in California. Many veterans of these trainings returned to southern California after the war and settled in the area. Today most of the land is managed by the BLM, and while only a few visible remnants of the DTC remain, the combination of history and rugged terrain attracts visitors. Remnants of Camp Ibis and Camp Clipper are accessible from Route 66. The Mojave Desert Heritage and Cultural Association rehabilitated a 1937 schoolhouse near Goffs, CA to create a research and education center that includes interpretation about the DTC.

Name: ARK at Blue Whale
Narrative: Zelta Davis and her husband created and managed this site. It closed in 1988 when the Davises were no longer able to continue managing the attraction. Hugh passed away in 1990 and Zelta in 2001.

Name: Blue Whale of Catoosa
Narrative: Hugh Davis constructed the Blue Whale in the early 70s for his wife Zelta as a surprise anniversary gift as she collected whale figurines. At first the site was just used by the family, but it was subsequently expanded to serve the public. Sand was added to create a beach, picnic tables were constructed, and lifeguards were hired. Davis continued to expand the site as “Nature’s Acres,” a roadside attraction, adding the A.R.K (Animal Reptile Kingdom). Davis’ brother-in-law, Acoma Indian Chief Wolf-Robe Hunt, ran the Arrowood Trading Post across the street.

Name: Blue Whale of Catoosa
Narrative: The famous Blue Whale of Catoosa gets decked out every Christmas season - he even pulls Santa's sleigh!

Name: Blue Whale of Catoosa
Narrative: The Blue Whale of Catoosa is a fun place to stop while driving Route 66.  It has a small shop there, picnic area, and of course, the big blue whale.  It is hard to stand in front of the whale and not return it big friendly smile!
Narrative_Src: Share Your Story: R Dean Larson

Name: Blue Whale of Catoosa
Narrative: The Blue Whale was built by Hugh S. Davis and completed in1972 as an anniversary gift to his wife, Zelta, on their 34th wedding anniversary.

Name: Blue Whale of Catoosa
Narrative: Visiting the Blue Whale was when it clicked for me: I began to understand why people LOVE Route 66 and why it holds such a unique place in American history books. The Blue Whale is most unique surprise anniversary gift I've ever heard of and it's impossible not to bust into a big smile while you pose with this icon of Route 66. The massive hand-built concrete-and-rebar structure was a surprise gift from Tulsa zoologist Hugh Davis to his wife in the 1970s.

Name: Bagdad Cafe
Narrative: The subject of a popular 1987 movie of the same name, the Bagdad Café was owned and managed by two women entrepreneurs over several decades. Originally known as the Sidewinder Café, the name was changed when Andrea Pruett took over from the previous owner, Shirley Trueman, and decided to take advantage of the notoriety from the movie (which had borrowed the name from another café down the road, since demolished). The Bagdad Café became a favorite stop for international travelers and the interior was covered with signs, photos, and memorabilia. COVID and its impacts on international travel forced the Bagdad Café to close in 2020. Since then it has suffered vandalism and Andrea Pruett has struggled with health issues.

Name: Bagdad Cafe
Narrative: Near the end of my first trip down The Mother Road in 2010, I was driving towards Barstow, looking for some dinner. Passing through Newberry Springs, I saw The Bagdad Cafe's open sign still on, but as I got out of the car, the sign went off. Wanting some pics, I grabbed my camera and fought the glare of the descending sun. As I framed my shot, a man walked out carrying a little girl. 'Do you want to come inside?' Of course I did. I followed him into what felt like a diner at the edge of the apocalypse, walls plastered with t-shirts and memorabilia, an old jukebox filling the air with distant music. I sat in a booth, closest to the door. Though closed, my host offered to fix me a meal. While I ate my Jack Palance burger, we chatted about his life there and my travels on 66. As I paid, I thanked him for his hospitality and for sacrificing his time and he handed me a pack of Cafe postcards, no charge.Random encounters like this make Route 66 more than just a road. It's an icon.

Name: Katherine Dunham Museum
Narrative:
Born in Chicago in 1909, Katherine Dunham was a prominent dancer, teacher, anthropologist, and civic activist. Her choreography incorporated Black traditions from around world. She founded the first Black modern dance troupe, and her performances 
and dance techniques became influential worldwide during the 1940s and 50s. A residency at Southern Illinois University in Carbondale led her to relocate to East St. Louis, where she purchased a residence and several other nearby homes, creating what became the Katherine Dunham Center for Arts and Humanities. The Center’s main building is a museum that contains African and Caribbean art objects from more than 50 countries. Located in a disinvested area containing many vacant lots and abandoned structures, the Center has struggled to achieve sustainability since Dunham’s death in 2006.

Name: La Posada Hotel
Narrative:
Designed by woman architect Mary Elizabeth Jane Colter, who created a fantasy vision/backstory for the site as “the grand hacienda of a wealthy Spanish landowner whose family lived here for 120 years, occasionally expanding the hotel until it final resembled the structure we see today.” La Posada was one of the Harvey hotels that hired single 
women, referred to as “Harvey girls,” known for their stellar service.

Name: From the Great Lakes to the Pacific Coast and the Gulf of Mexico along the Santa Fe
La Posada Hotel
Narrative: A Harvey Railroad Hotel - One of America's great hotels.  Have gone out of our way to stay there twice, and we live 2,000 miles away.  Not far from the great Meteor Crater, and Acoma Pueblo.

Name: Rock Café
Narrative: Originally opened in 1939, and was a Greyhound bus stop and at one point was open 24 hours a day. Current proprietor Dawn Welch is a Route 66 mainstay and was the basis for the character “Sally Carrera” in the Pixar movie Cars. She was 24 years old when she started at the Rock Café and has been running it for 29 years. She has overcome considerable adversity as a business owner, carrying out extensive rehab work in the early 90s after acquiring the building, surviving a major tornado that hit Stroud in 1999 and devastated the local economy, and rebuilding in a preservation sensitive way after the building was heavily damaged by a fire in 2008. She was named Oklahoma Woman of the Year in 2009. Partially American Indian owned?

Name: Threatt Filling Station and Family Farm
Narrative: This 1915 gas station was the only known Black owned and operated owned and operated filling station during the Jim Crow era, making it a save haven for Black travelers. It is still owned by the same family. The Threatts homesteaded in the Luther area after it was opened up for settlement in 1889. The NPS states: “the Threatts saw Oklahoma land as a great opportunity. They joined former slaves of local Cherokee, Choctaw, Chicksaw, Creek and Seminole owners as well as former staves from the southeast. In seeking greater security, economic opportunity, and racial solidarity in Oklahoma.” While not officially listed in the Green Book, it was one of a very few places where people of color were welcomed. The family recalls that Tulsans fleeing the 1921 Race Massacre found refuge at the Threatt Farm.

Name: Historic Threatt Filling Station
Narrative: The Threatt Filling Station is an important site for all of Route 66 as it was a Black owned-and-operated station during the Jim Crow era. The family has been working diligently for years to restore the station (which closed in the 1970s) as an interpretive center.

Name: Cool Springs Station
Narrative: The Cool Springs Cabins and Cafe were abandoned and in ruin when they were purchased in 2001 and restoration was begun.  The rebuilt Cool Springs station is now a gift shop offering Route 66 souvenirs and one of a kind Cool Springs memorabilia.  Future plans include rebuilding the classic cafe.  This is a little gem on the old road between Kingman and Oatman, AZ.
Narrative_Src: Share Your Story: R. Dean Larson

Name: Meteor City Gilbert Ortega dome
Narrative: My introduction to Route 66 started in the late 70s when my father was transferred. We moved west on Rt66, But the Rt 66 signs that were already gone. We never completed the Route, so my travels started in the west.There are so many memories, happy and sad, of Route 66.  I try to make more each year by traveling it, meeting interesting people, supporting the small businesses, and helping the Route 66 Associations. My photo, of the Meteor City Gilbert Ortega dome, (2018). My first visit (late 70s), it was busy with local crafts and Indian jewelry. The world's longest map of Route 66 stretched to the east. It was featured in the movie Star Man.Later visits resulted in the same stuff from China that you find at everywhere.So much of the Historic Route has deteriorated. Kudos to all those who are stepping up to save what is left! Even if you can't travel to a Route 66 business, they will greatly appreciate your support online.

Name: Jack Rabbit Trading Post
Narrative: In the late 50's we would drive from Barstow, CA to Many, LA to visit our grandparents.  My dad was a Marine and stationed at the Marine Corps Logisitc Base in Barstow.  We traveled on Route 66 for most of this trip and for my brother and I we always loved the "Trading Posts" along the route where they sold touristy trinkets and were the precursor to "Rest Stops" of today.  In an old Chevy Sedan equipped with a window air conditioner and water bag tied to the front we endured the heat of the southwestern deserts in Arizona and New Mexico and would beg to stop at these posts.  This was one of our favorites and we have plenty of ancient photos just like this one to prove it.

Narrative: Sunset at Westside Lilo's in Seligman, Arizona

Name: Westside Lilo's Cafe
Narrative: Lilo and Pat Russell moved to Seligman in 1962 from Wiesbaden Germany.  Pat was raised in Seligman Arizona and after his time in the Army, wanted to return to his home town to start his family.  Lilo had always dreamed of opening a business on Route 66 and longed to have a place that offered good quality food and some of her German specialties.  In May of 1996, Lilo purchased a restaurant that was closed in the early 80s and with the help of her husband Pat and eldest daughter Nancy, Westside Lilo's Cafe opened for business in June of 1996.  Soon after opening, Lilo's other daughter, Brenda joined the family operation.  Westside Lilo's quickly became a favorite of the locals and many people who travel Historic Route 66 on a regular basis. Lilo's' daily specials, giant cinnamon rolls and carrot cake, continue to drive repeat business, and the restaurant today has quite a following.

Narrative: My wife Traci and I traveled Route 66 in June, 2023. Route 66 goes right through Petrified Forest National Park, so we took the time to see much of the park. It really gives a person perspective when you think about how the petrified wood was alive over 200 million years ago.

Name: Midpoint Cafe Route 66
Narrative: Exactly halfway between Chicago and L.A. is the Midpoint Cafe.  We had breakfast there, and as we were seated at our Formica topped retro table eavesdropping on two guys in overalls talking about their farms, four major league Harleys pulled into the parking lot, each with a couple of riders.  They came into the cafe speaking German and headed straight for the gift shop.  We looked at the visitor sign-in book, and found that people from literally every country in the world have stopped into the Midpoint Cafe for food or gifts.  Amazing place -- great food, and a melting pot for local, national, and international visitors!
Narrative_Src: Share Your Story: R. Dean Larson

Name: Midpoint Cafe Route 66
Narrative: This is a must stop photo op! The Midpoint Cafe sits at the half way point between Chicago and Santa Monica. Their burgers are fabulous and the Route 66 is a challenge any hungry traveler would love to sit down to, and then, they will serve you up their famous Ugly Crust Pie. Stop in, visit, eat and shop. My friendship with the workers at the cafe has been life changing ever since I moved to the TX Panhandle. They all inspired me to get involved with Route 66, join the associations and make life long connections.

Name: Midpoint Cafe Route 66

Narrative: While driving through the Painted Desert en route to the Petrified Forest in mid-July 2010, we spotted this fine specimen, a jumping cholla cactus with full blooms at the top and ripening fruit below. Its name reflects the fact that the slightest brush against the plant will leave some barbed cactus spines, or even a whole segment, firmly attached to one's clothing or skin. Recalling a previous nasty encounter with a fishhook barrel cactus, I approached this cholla just close enough to take its portrait. Pretty in its own way, isn't it!

Name: 1869 Round Barn
Narrative: The Arcadia Round Barn is a landmark and tourist attraction on historic U.S. Route 66 in Arcadia, Oklahoma, United States. It was built by local farmer William Harrison Odor using native bur oak boards soaked while green and forced into the curves needed for the walls and roof rafters.
Narrative_Src: Share Your Story: R. Dean Larson

I very much enjoy telling visitors about the acoustics and the ceiling in the loft.

Name: Williams, Arizona
Narrative: My wife and I visited Williams, Arizona in July of 2021!  While this may not be an old story of Route 66, it is still a wonderful memory of an historic place in our lives.  I retired from full time work in March of 2021 and we moved to Gilbert, Arizona, to be closer to my wife's parents (I call them my in-loves since I am in love with their daughter), since they were now in their 80's and we wanted to be of service to them.  My wife planned a trip for us to the Grand Canyon, about 30 miles north of Williams.  Williams is on Route 66 as the last stop in Arizona going west. My wife booked us a room in the Sheridan Inn, a  Bed and Breakfast in Williams that was absolutely stunning and outstanding in terms of food and lodging and we will stay there again at some point in our lives!  This was my first trip to the Grand Canyon and we took a 45 minute helicopter tour and a walking tour of a few different places in the national park.  I walked around Williams to see the sites and love it.

Big Boy's Auto Court
Status_Note: Built in 1937 by Al "Big Boy" Murphy, this court consisted of four wood-frame "modern" cabins, along with a Bar-B-Q stand and station. It proved popular and Big Boy was soon expanding. The enlarged court had "Twelve units, strictly modern, some with Frigidaires and cooking facilities. Modern Bar-B-Q restaurant - Super service station - Ice cream gardens and fountain. Two minutes to theater and shopping district. One price to all." The sign appealed "Hi there. Stop. We've been looking for you today." After expanding to 18 units, it became the Sands Motel in 1959. Razed in 1972.

Name: Winslow, Arizona, Looking East from Business Center
Winslow, Arizona, East on U. S. Hwy. 66
Winslow, AZ, USA
Narrative: What a privilege to traverse the road that holds so much space in our minds alongside your best friend... not just once, but twice. I have been on two great American road trips, both with my best friend. Trips that rival those of Jack Kerouac, or rather, are inspired by life on the road. Route 66 carries our dreams and our memories. Against the asphalt and a painted yellow line, I have learned that the road inspires introspection, authenticity, and laughter. Driving across the United States, while on its most famous road, anyone can feel inspired by their dreams and drive towards them in a very real way. Dreaming along the road with one's best friend is no different -- I couldn't think of a more-preferred trio. Most recently, we drove to Winslow, AZ to stand on a corner like eagles, only to take it easy and indulge in an ice cream cone. However, the road...it calls us, and we traded our stillness for the reality of perpetual motion on the illustrious Route 66.

Name: Bob John's Brandtville
Status_Note: the restaurant opened in 1957, cannot find a date of demolition
Narrative: Until the mid-1960s, college girls at Illinois Wesleyan in Bloomington, IL had hours. So, on Friday and Saturday nights at midnight, all the fraternity boys dropped their girls off and headed straight for Bob John's Brandtville for the Trucker's Special. Located on Route 66 on the southeast side of town, late at night the restaurant was a unique mix of over the road drivers, weary travelers and college boys full of themselves. But they all had one thing in common: Bob Johnson's 24-hour-a-day breakfast. Time moved on: Girls' hours ended, boys became men, and some went to Viet Nam.  Brandtville eventually closed and 66 was replaced by 55. The memories linger on for those of a certain age.

Narrative: I drove the majority of Route 66 when I moved from California to the East Coast. With a rented minivan full of all my possessions, including my cat and dog, I marveled at how vast and endless the roadway seemed against the horizon. At stops along the drive, I would walk each pet for a bit and particularly noted how curious my cat was about this new expansive scenery.Fast forward several days to an overnight stop in Oklahoma, and that curiousity was unstoppable, apparently. Mushi the cat crept unnoticed out of the motel room and into the night, never to been seen again.I like to think of her living the rest of her time along the route, enjoying the space, roaming free.

Name: Cadillac Ranch
Narrative: Cadillac Ranch was invented and built by a group of art-hippies imported from San Francisco. They called themselves The Ant Farm, and their silent partner was an Amarillo billionaire. He wanted a piece of public art that would baffle the locals, and the hippies came up with a tribute to the evolution of the Cadillac tail fin.  Since their installation, visitors have been welcome to 'decorate' them with spray paint.  Definitely worth the stop!
Narrative_Src: Share Your Story: R. Dean Larson

Name: Cadillac Ranch
Narrative: Our first family road trip to California from Mississippi and the Cadillac Ranch was one of our first stops on Route 66! We traveled for 1 week and it was a beautiful experience to share with our daughters. The history of this route and the scenic drive has provided wonderful memories for my family and I. This road trip will always be memorable for our girls. They learned so much and asked questions that they didn't even know they had. We can't wait to do this again.

Name: Cadillac Ranch
Narrative: On my Route 66 end-to-end drive, leaving Amarillo, Texas I very quickly had to stop for a shot of the famous Cadillac Ranch.  These ten Caddys range through the ?tail-fin? years, from 1948 to 1964.  It was a nostalgic moment, as I remembered my own 1962 mauve Sedan DeVille (very finny, with all-leather mauve interior!).  I bought it in 1970 for $175, and drove it for a couple of years as it gradually died.  Memorable.  Anyway, Cadillac Ranch is a wonderfully odd work of art.

Oatman, Arizona
Narrative: In 1952, when I was 6, my family moved from the LA area to Toronto.  My Dad made a detour to Las Vegas - he was a gambler - but we joined Route 66 again in Kingman.  We took Route 66 most all the way to the Chicago area.  I remember going through Albuquerque, Amarillo - a big dust storm - and Tulsa.  My father took some 8 mm movies, and got a shot of a sign on Route 66, that read "Flagstaff 27". He also took a shot of Mt Humphreys and the highway in the distance.  In 2002, my wife and I drove Route 66 from Williams to Oatman, We played various artists singing "Get Your Kicks on Route 66."  What else?  We took a detour to Interstate 40, and found a sign that said "Flagstaff 28".  Close enough.  The road was changed; the forest had changed; but Mt Humphreys was in the same place.  It was great to be near the spot my Dad had filmed, 50 years earlier.  When we got back to Tempe, I dubbed Natalie Cole singing Route 66 to the videos we shot.

Name: Oatman, Arizona
Narrative: My sister and I traveled the route from Chicago to the Santa Monica Pier to celebrate my 66th birthday.   I see a couple of my favorite spots - The Blue Swallow, LaPosada, etc.  But I think the most place to visit with Oatman, Arizona.   We saw a "gun fight" in the street and were amused feeding the wild burros.  A special spot on the route for sure!

Name: Oatman, AZ
Narrative: Founded around 1902, Oatman lies approximately 30 minutes from Needles, CA (border). With a population of 87, it's a unique small town stop where Route 66 travelers can stretch their legs, explore an old west town, mail postcards to friends, and stock up on water and souvenirs. Wild burros roam Main Street, seeking food from locals and travelers. Feeding the burrows is strictly prohibited, but their presence adds to the town's appeal. Note: Mind the burro droppings and urine. Bonus. Depending on your arrival time, if you're not busy perusing the historic buildings, keep an eye out for a good old-fashioned Wild West faux shootout in the middle of Main Street. Photos: c. 2014

Name: Chain of Rocks Bridge
Narrative: This is one of my favorite stories to tell! This was my second trip from my hometown Dwight, IL all the way to the Missouri border in Madison. I had seen a picture of the Chain of Rocks bridge from a different angle and I found a way to give that a try. I went to the Mississippi River shore and learned two lessons. One, do not go down to the muddy Mississippi after a day of rain. Two, do not wear flip-flops in said mud. I ended up getting stuck in the mud but ended up taking this picture in that very spot, so being stuck was very much worth it. Having feet coated in mud also gave me the advantage of not having small rocks poke me on the way back to my car. I ended up capturing a gorgeous sunset as well on the way back home.

Name: Chain of Rocks Bridge
Narrative: My wife and I took a weekend trip along the National Road, Lincoln Highway, and Route 66 for inspiration and photography -- Ohio, Indiana, and Illinois. Along 66, we visited the Launching Pad, Funk's Grove for Sirup, ate at the Ariston, and ended up at the Chain of Rocks Bridge along the Mother Road in Illinois. Inspiration and photos were used for my albums, Rivers of Asphalt and The Father Road. I wanted to express my feelings of a lost era throughout both albums, but not a nostalgic take, something closer to Kraftwerk meets Pink Floyd. Bob Waldmire was interested in my project and provided him some of the music to inspire his planned cover art, which he loved, but he sadly passed before I finished the record. We ended up using a shot from the Chain of Rocks Bridge for the cover. Nevertheless, receiving a surprise phone call from Bob remains one of the highlights of my life. Rivers of Asphalt was dedicated to Bob and my parents in the liner notes for the album.

Name: Dell Rhea's Chicken Basket
Narrative: I attended college full-time and I lived in the same state as my grandma at the time. We'd always find a way to have lunch together once a semester and one of these times, we chose the Chicken Basket in Willowbrook. I had always ordered the same thing, which was this baked macaroni and cheese with jalapeños, bacon, and onions (it was so good!!) and I decided to also order an orange cream soda that literally tasted like a dreamsicle. Our table was by the fireplace, and as it was January and quite cold in Illinois, it was worth snapping a picture of the moment.

Name: Tucumcari's Pow Wow Diner and Lizard Lounge
Narrative: In 2022, we traveled from Tucson to Tucumcari, NM (following the route laid out in "Willin,'" recorded by Tucson native Linda Ronstadt.) We stayed in Tucumcari on Route 66 overnight, and discovered the Pow Wow Restaurant and Lizard Lounge, which had amazingly naturalistic murals of patrons painted in each booth. Our waitress told us the poignant story of two widows who dined there weekly so they could have dinner with their husbands, now immortalized on the walls of the restaurant. By the time we returned in 2023, the restaurant was permanently closed.
Narrative_Src: Share Your Story: Nancy M Burton

Name: Copper Cart Restaurant
Narrative: Route 66 was a historic highway that connected the West Coast to the Midwest. Louise Brown was born and raised in Seligman, AZ. In Seligman, AZ, Louise Brown ran the famous diner, the Copper Cart Restaurant. She witnessed the changes that came with the highway and remained optimistic. However, the construction of a bypass on the highway eventually caused her diner to suffer. Despite this, Louise kept her diner running for many years, preserving the spirit of Route 66 and her love for her hometown.After raising five children, she made the difficult decision to sell the restaurant. Thanks to the efforts of many residents surrounding Route 66, more and more travelers are now visiting these small towns and revitalizing Route 66. Route 66 represents a time when things were simpler, with a small town atmosphere and way of life. Seligman, is a charming little town that embodies all the wonderful things about small town living - love, friendship, and a community that values neighbors.

Most recent reports from Route 66 News (https://www.route66news.com/2024/11/26/former-hotel-blue-in-albuquerque-expected-to-reopen-in-early-2025/) that the building was set to reopen in first quarter of 2025. It is unclear the extent to which the rest of the hotel is open.

Name: Munger Moss Motel
Narrative: Since 1946, the Munger Moss Hotel has been providing accommodation for Route 66 travelers. The motel initially consisted of separate cabins, but as the business continued to grow the gaps between the cabins were filled in to create more units. In 1957, Route 66 was rerouted bypassing the motel. As a result, Pete Hudson, the owner, built a makeshift bridge over a ditch to provide travelers easy access to the motel from the new alignment of Route 66. The motel's iconic sign, which has welcomed guests for decades, was restored with the assistance of The Neon Heritage Preservation Committee, The Route 66 Association of Missouri and The National Park Service.

Name: Munger Moss Motel
Narrative: This was taken in 2018 when I spent the night in Lebanon, MO with my dad, my grandma, and a friend. We did not spend the night at the Munger Moss Motel, but we did stop by, take pictures, and talk to Ramona, who was very sweet and full of knowledge. I did not sleep in the Munger Moss Motel until September 2023 with my husband after Ramona passed, and it turned out to be one of the best experiences I ever had on Route 66.

Name: Nelson's Old Riverton Store
Narrative: For nearly a century the Nelson's Old Riverton Store, originally known as the Williams Store and later the Eisler Bros. Old Riverton Store, has been a gathering place for nearby residents and a popular stop for Route 66 travelers. The business was established in 1925 after its owner, WWI veteran Leo Williams constructed the building. Although the store has changed hands multiple times it has continually operated as a market offering a variety of goods such as produce, flowers, local crafts, and Route 66 memorabilia. The store's interior has remained largely unchanged, with many original features still intact, including its pressed ceiling tiles and deli counter. Recognizing its historical significance, the distinctive vernacular building was placed on the National Register of Historic Places in 2003.

Name: Tulsa, OK
Narrative: Many members of the Moore family, and also of the Willis family lived in Tulsa, which we lived in Norman.  Trips to Tulsa were always along Route 66, with stops for ice cream or to buy some FRANKOMA pottery were every six months.
Narrative_Src: Share Your Story: Willis H A Moore

Name: Tulsa, OK
Narrative: My grandparents, Ben and Alzada Tadlock were nicknamed Big Momma and Big Daddy by the eldest of my sixteen first cousins. When I was born in 1954, the 'Bigs' lived in Norman, Oklahoma, and owned a neighborhood store, Tadlock Grocery. Within a week of my birth at Chanute AFB, Rantoul, Illinois, the Bigs drove over 700 miles in one day, on the Mother Road to come see me. Stopping for gas outside St. Louis, Missouri, Big Momma fell in love with a little clock on sale at a gas station. The clock was fashioned as a cottage with a big picture window and a little gray-haired lady with a bun, sitting in a rocking chair. That beloved clock sat on their fireplace mantel for as long as I can remember, mesmerizing generations of small children. As a nomadic military family, our yearly pilgrimage to the Bigs felt like coming home and although I do not remember that first meeting, every time I look at my Rock'n Granny clock, I remember the loving warmth of my Grandparent?s happy home.
Narrative_Src: Share Your Story: Donna Lynn Hickman

Name: San José de la Laguna Mission Church and Convento Historic Site
Narrative: Spread across a rise north of present Interstate 40 is the picturesque Pueblo of Laguna, home to the Western Keres puebloan people whose reservation lands extend westward from Albuquerque. The white stucco edifice of San Jose de Laguna Church centers the village as it has for some 325 years. We have respectfully visited there a couple of times. Most often, though, we interstate travelers whoosh past at a distance, unless stopping by the blue roadside stands if ladies of the pueblo have appeared with fresh-baked bread for sale.

Name: New Haven Courts 1
Status_Note: New Haven Courts, one of the earliest Route 66 courts on Glenstone, opened in 1938 with 12 cabins ($3 up), boasting "all strictly modern, fireproof, steam heated by central plant. Air cooled. Sleep safely." New Haven Courts was renamed the Ship & Anchor Motel in 1953. Expanding to 34 units, the native rock cabins were remodeled, more units built and connected with a new facade in front, and removed the filling station. In the early 1960s, the Ship & Anchor added a swimming pool in its courtyard, and television in its rooms. It became the Ozark Motel in 1981. Razed in 1999.

Name: Flatbed Ford, Winslow, Arizona
Narrative: Most everyone takes a picture "standing on a corner in Winslow, Arizona", but as I stood on the corner, I noticed the next part of the verse ("it's a girl my Lord in a flatbed Ford") parked just up the street.  I couldn't resist getting that photograph to represent Winslow!

Name: Western Motel and the "Big Indian"
Narrative: The Western Motel dates back to the 1950s (when it also had overnight stables on offer) but the giant fiberglass Native American Chief was saved from destruction in Massachusetts. It was fully restored and moved to the Sooner State.

Name: Western Motel
Narrative: A 20-unit motel located 2 miles west of Vinita, OK on Route 66. Clean, safe and affordable, rooms are rented nightly, weekly or by the month.  All rooms were completely refurbished in 2021/2022.  Several rooms have been remodeled with Route 66 travelers in mind with all Route 66 decor and bedding. Each room come with all furnishings, linens, mini fridge, microwave, TV and Wi-Fi. The motel is open year around and is also located next door to the Hi-Way Cafe.

Status_Note: U Drop Inn, featured on the postcard, closed in the 1990s but was purchased by the First National Bank of Shamrock after it was listed on the National Register of Historic Places. The bank then donated it to the city of Shamrock who restored it and has turned it into a museum.

Name: Steve's Cafe
Narrative: William Wilson moved to Chenoa, IL from Kentucky in 1949 when he was 16 years old. He got a job at the Texaco station located on Route 66 which was attached to Steve?s Café. Willie worked 10 pm to 7 am 7 days a week for $35. He met Norma Kiper shortly after taking that job. She used get gas just to see Willie; and he would ?clean the windshield profusely while trying to charm her?. They will celebrate their 73rd anniversary June 19, 2024.Willie recalls that one night in 1949 while he was working waitresses from Steve?s Café came into the station saying there was trouble and needed his help. He ran into the café and found that a man had the owner, Steve Wilcox, up against the wall in the kitchen area with a butcher knife to his throat. Willie talked continuously to the guy to try to stall for awhile. Police officer, Jerry Gillespie, showed up and told the man, who obviously had been drinking, to put the knife down, and he did. Mr. Wilcox always thanked Willie for saving his life.

Name: The Flame
Status_Note:
The Flame still has a pin on Google Maps, but it is listed as permanently closed. Since the postcard shows only the interior of the restaurant, it is difficult to tell if the building currently at the site (the City of Countryside Municipal Complex) is the original or a new one. The restaurant's old Facebook page was active as recently as 2024, but the website below notes that the City of Countryside Municipal Complex was built with a LEED certification, making it unlikely that the city government simply took over the old restaurant building. I suspect it is a new build.

https://www.brickworkssupply.com/inspiration-resources/articles/city-of-countryside-municipal-complex

Name: Wagon Wheel Motel
Narrative: We stayed at the Wagon Wheel Motel in Cuba, MO.  Very cute little bit of Route 66 history.  It is also located next door to the Missouri Hicks restaurant that has some killer BBQ!  Combined with an amazing thunder and lightning storm for a very exciting evening!

Name: Wagon Wheel Motel
Narrative: Since 1936, the Wagon Wheel Motel has captivated Route 66 travelers as the oldest continuously operated motel along the route. The property features a cafe and station where guests could enjoy meals and refuel their vehicles before embarking on their journey to experience more of Route 66. Buildings original to the property were constructed with local Ozark sandstone and reflect the Tudor Revival style. During the 1940s, the iconic Wagon Wheel neon sign that welcomes travelers was erected. In 2003, the motel was listed on the National Register of Historic Places and today the former gas station and cafe house the gift shop.

Name: Carthage, MO, USA
Narrative: Warm, summer, weekend nights were always spent at the drive-in. Children playing on the playground equipment just below the screen, speakers hanging on car windows, the refreshment center full of anxious snackers. Not to mention the great movie and sometimes a second that would play all night under the summer stars. Most of these drive-in movie theaters are long-gone but one still shows regularly on old Route 66 in Carthage, Missouri. This painting was created by artist  Andy Thomas of Carthage, Missouri.
Narrative_Src: Share Your Story: Andy Thomas Fine Art

Name: Wigwam Motel
Narrative: The Wigwam Motels, also known as the "Wigwam Villages", is a motel chain in the United States built during the 1930s and 1940s. The rooms are built in the form of tipis, mistakenly referred to as wigwams.  Having the vintage cars parked by the "wigwams" is a really nice touch!
Narrative_Src: Share Your Story: R. Dean Larson

Name: Wigwam Motel
Narrative: When my husband and I were dating, we had a conversation over dinner about how we both wanted to drive Route 66, and soon we started to lightly plan a trip--this was the first time we envisioned anything in the future together. A few years later we took two weeks off of work and drove from Chicago to LA on our honeymoon, with a stop at the Grand Canyon. We eschewed GPS in favor of old school maps and stopped at every attraction we could. In this photo you can see our wedding-decorated car at in Holbrook, Arizona. Over the past 7 years when we've told people about our honeymoon they always say it sounds so "us," and countless people have told us how they've dreamed of a similar trip. I have so many fond memories from the trip, so Route 66 makes me think of being hopeful and in love.

Name: Wigwam Motel
Narrative: In October of 2014, I had the opportunity to travel Route 66 , from East to West, with my uncle and a family friend. Best 10 days ever. Of course, one picture cannot say it all, but this location was one of my favorites.

Name: Stewart's Petrified Wood Shop
Narrative: The rainbow-colored, 200 million-year-old stone tree trunks that litter Petrified Forest National Park and the surrounding area have fascinated generations of visitors. Of course, snatching samples of the beautiful fossils is strictly forbidden. But tourists can readily find all the petrified wood they could want at commercial shops both inside and outside the park boundaries. These establishments obtain quantities of the material from deposits on private lands. They can supply rough chunks for landscaping or decorating, as well as beautifully cut and polished jewelry and souvenir items of smaller scale. We found this lumber yard just south of Holbrook, Arizona, in 2010. It had acres of natural specimens outside and a shop with more varied offerings inside.

Name: Historic Grand Canyon Hotel
Narrative: Originally established in 1891, this hotel once catered to a diverse array of guests and dignitaries, serving as the final stop on the journey to the Grand Canyon. However, with the construction of the I-40 highway bypassing the town of Williams in the 1970s, the hotel fell into disrepair, mirroring the decline of the once-thriving town. In 2004, the town council mandated the sale of the hotel, prompting substantial investments to restore its former splendor. Under new ownership, the hotel has undergone another meticulous renovation, seamlessly blending timeless Victorian aesthetics with modern amenities to offer guests an immersive historic experience. Book a room at the Historic Grand Canyon Hotel and immerse yourself in the rich legacy of Route 66 firsthand.

Name: Deck's Drug Store & Docs Just Off 66
Narrative: Deck's Drug Store opened in March of 1884. It was ran by three generations of the Deck's family until 2001. Between 2001 in 2021 they were several different owners. In December 2021, Steve and Casey Claypool purchased the old fashioned soda fountain, remodeled and renovated it, and put all of the antique pharmacy items on display and re-opened the business under Docs Just Off 66. Today, Docs Just Off 66 pays homage to the Deck family that ran this historic business for over 117 years. This past year, the business celebrated 140 years; it is currently the longest operating business in the city of Girard.  Now, it?s open seven days a week, serving lunch, dinner, and classic old fashioned treats from the original soda fountain that was installed in 1929.

Name: Cozy Dog Drive In
Narrative: Since 1949, Cozy Dog Drive In has been serving Route 66 Travelers and local residents the  original hotdog on a stick. Formerly known as crusty curs these cozy dogs are dipped in a batter that was perfected in 1946 and then deep fried to perfection. The business was started by U.S. Air Force Veteran Ed Waldmire Jr. And today the business is run by his grandson who is keeping the tradition of the Cozy Dog Drive In alive.

Name: Funks Grove Pure Maple Sirup Farm
Funks Grove Pure Maple Sirup Farm
Narrative: In the summer of 2008 I took my children down Route 66 since they grew up in London, I figured they needed to see how big and diverse America was in every corner.  It was eye opening fun for us all.  Our favorite place is Funk's Grove Pure Maple Syrup in Illinois which was near where we were living in Chicago.  This photo depicts our UK relatives in Funk's Grove in January 2014.  Extraordinary!

Name: Funks Grove Pure Maple Sirup
Narrative: For 132 years Funks Grove Pure Maple Sirup has provided homemade maple syrup to local residents and later to travelers following the establishment of Route 66 in 1926. The Funk family, who established a settlement in 1824 in the area that later became known as Funks Grove, began producing maple syrup on their farm as it was the only sweetener available in rural Illinois. The long-standing tradition of procuring sap from maple trees was first done by Native Americans. In 1891, the Funks began commercially producing maple syrup and to this day the business continues to be owned by the Funk family. The business is located within a 35-year-old sugar house that is attached to a portion of a former sugar house built c. 1930. The business proudly displays a sign along the route featuring its distinctive spelling of "sirup," guiding travelers to their establishment.

Name: Henry's Rabbit Ranch
Image_Cr: Carol M. Highsmith, Library of Congress

Name: Henrys Rabbit Ranch
Narrative: Henrys Ra66it Ranch started as Route 66 Souvenir/Info center for past, present and future roadies. Located on the 1930-1940 alignment. Has always been rabbit themed, using VW Rabbits and the bunny rabbit type. Quirkiness at its best to garner one's interest to see what it is all about. One is usually greeted by a counter bunny eager to offer a free autograph for the inquiring traveler. Souvenir's of gift shops of bygone eras are available from postcards, themed t-shirts, bumper stickers, etc. Even the dust on the counter and parking lot is original. People continually ask when the Station dates back to, thinking the late 30's-40's. It's a reproduction time machine of. Once in the 90's the EPA asked if the tanks were still in the ground. We have at present the largest bunny, being 8' tall, on all of Route 66. Outside and inside is trucking memorabilia of the long defunct Campbell 66 Express Trucking Co. Consists of one road tractor and three semi-trailers along with others. Hop in !!
Narrative_Src: Share Your Story: Richard M Henry Sr

Name: Henrys Rabbit Ranch
Narrative: We didn't know Henry Rich from Staunton, but we quickly became acquainted and a friendship grew between us. We will not forget the gift made by Henry in the form of old US license plates.There are many other very welcoming characters along Route 66! That?s what attracts me there!

Name: Rialto Square Theatre
Narrative: Since 1926, the Baroque architecture of the Rialto Square Theatre has captivated Route 66 travelers. Originally designed and operated as a vaudeville movie palace, this grand structure, also known as the 'jewel of Joliet,' now hosts a variety of events including plays, concerts and musicals. The ornate building, designed by prominent theatre architects C. W. and George Rapp, was listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 1978.

Name: The Ariston Cafe
Narrative: This was THE day the neon lights at the Ariston Cafe turned back on after they were restored. I attended the relighting ceremony after making a trip through Illinois?s Red Carpet Corridor and had quite the adventure that ended with this stunning display. This is one of my favorite restaurants to dine in Illinois.

Name: Cars on the Route
Narrative: Cars on the Route, located in Galena, Kansas, stands out as one of the most memorable stops along Route 66. In 1934, the former Kan-O-Tex Service Station was built and before its 2007 restoration, the property was abandoned for decades. The property was purchased by four local women who sought to revitalize the small part of Route 66 that passes through Kansas. They artfully named the station Four Women on the Route and operated it as a gift shop before the business changed hands. Cars on the Route is home to Tow Tater, a 1951 international boom truck, which served as the inspiration for the well-known animated character Tow Mater from the beloved movie Cars.

Name: Cars on the Route
Narrative: In 2006, four women ceased the opportunity to get travelers to visit their little section of the Mother Road in Kansas. "Tow Tater" the 1951 International L-170 Series Boom truck and the inspiration for Animated "Cars" character "Mater" sits outside a restored circa 1938 Kan-O-Tex Station in Galena, Kansas.

Name: Spencer Station
Narrative: In 1925, Sidney Casey heard of a 'brand new highway' coming through Spencer MO. He walked 55 miles to get to Spencer to purchase 2 acres of property and an old wooden general store for $500. He build the 'new' brick General Store in 1926, the gas station and garage in 1927 and the Cafe / Barber Shop in 1928. He ran is successfully until Route 66 was bypassed in 1961, in which Sidney closed do doors for good.In 2007, the Ryans purchased it from Sidney's grandson Kent (Kent was the third generation of Casey to own it from 1925 until 2007). The Ryan's put a new roof on several of the buildings, added the canopies and gas pump island with vintage Phillip 66 gas pumps. But they never really opened it to the public as it was more of 'their place'.In 2022, Ed Klein of Route 66 World purchased the buildings from the Ryans and is working on a full restoration to bring the buildings back to how they were in the 30s and 40s. The buildings are open for visitors most weekend.

Name: Carthage Deli
Narrative: Since 1979, Carthage Deli has served local costumers and Route 66 travelers. The current owners purchased the business, which is located in a brick structure that was built in 1884 that is known as the old Carthage Bank building, in 1998 from the founders of the deli. The deli is well loved by the local community and every morning at 7 a.m. loyal patrons arrive for their cup of coffee. A long-standing tradition of the business is free brownie Tuesday and when visiting the deli for breakfast, lunch or dinner, customers are welcomed by the deli's 1950s décor.
