Name: ROUTE 66 Pole Banners and Sign Restoration for Ted Drewes Frozen Custard
Donut Drive-In
Narrative: Since 1953, Donut Drive-In has been serving locals and Route 66 travelers sweet treats. These donuts have been voted the best donuts along Route 66 and although the business has changed hands the original family recipes are still utilized. In 2020, a local husband and wife duo, who often indulged in these donuts during their childhood, purchased the business. With the help of the employees who have worked there for decades, the couple is determined to keep the business and its longstanding traditions alive. During its 70-year lifespan, the business has continued to operate in its original 600 square foot building and its vintage neon sign has remained a beacon in the community.

Name: Rockwood Motor Court
Image_Cr: Carol M. Highsmith, Library of Congress

Name: Rockwood Motor Court
Narrative: Constructed in 1929 with Ozark sandstone and red bricks, the business now known as Rockwood Motor Court originally served as a Tourist Camp for Route 66 travelers. Featuring six cabins, a filling station, a cafe and a single-car garage, all of which are original to the property, Rockwood Motor Court is recognized as the oldest operating court on Route 66. Recently renovated, each motel room reflects a different era of Route 66's history through its vintage decor, furniture and memorabilia.

Name: Spencer's Grill
Narrative: Spencer's Grill in Kirkwood, Missouri is a 1940s-era diner that has survived multiple ownership changes while keeping the original aesthetic (and deliciousness) intact.

Name: Boots Court Motel
Image_Cr: Carol M. Highsmith, Library of Congress

Name: Boots Court Motel
Narrative: Since 1939, Boots Court Motel has been a popular destination for Route 66 travelers. The motel, which originally charged $2.50 per night, is well-known for hosting Old Hollywood actor Clark Gable as an overnight guest. In the early 2000s, the motel was in danger of being demolished, but after an outcry from preservation groups, the Boots Court Motel and its Streamline Moderne architecture was saved. In 2021, the Boots Court Motel Foundation was established and the following year the motel was listed on the National Register of Historic Places. A former gas station adjacent to the property now serves as the Boots Court Motel Visitors Center.

Name: Boots Court Motel
Narrative: Boots Court is one of those places that makes it easy to imagine yourself in a different time. It is without question one of the coolest and most authentically vintage places we stayed on our entire Route 66 journey in 2017. Sure, the radio and lights aren't original, but there are none of the modern distractions that make it so easy to ignore what's around you. It's obvious that the restoration of the motel had been thoughtfully done in an effort to truly recreate the experience of a 1949 traveler. Our room had a radio but not a TV. Why? Because the town of Carthage didn't get television until 1953. Was the bed the most comfortable we've ever slept in? No, but that doesn't matter when you open the door with an actual key or pull up the era-appropriate chenille bedspread. The best part of our stay, however, was the evening, which we spent playing gin rummy and sipping wine from plastic cups while listening to '40s tunes. Definitely a night we'll remember forever.

Narrative: Teepee Curios in Tucumcari, New Mexico has two different spellings (Teepee on the building, Tepee on the neon sign) and has been selling curios along Route 66 for decades.

Name: Tee Pee Curio
Narrative: Definitely designed to attract tourists' attention, much original Route 66 commercial architecture in Arizona and New Mexico featured bold Indian themes, some a bit misplaced geographically or even a tad stereotypical by modern sensibilities. Tee Pee Curio is a prime example of Route 66 kitsch at its very apex. Most Native American communities in the pre-Spanish Southwest preferred permanent pueblo villages over portable buffalo hide lodges, but let's not quibble. Tee Pee Curio is one of the few vintage Route 66 era survivors that we can visit, and its proudly-maintained exterior leaves little doubt as to what one might expect inside. Unfortunately, the shop was closed when we took this shot one Sunday morning in 2019.

Name: Teepee Curios
Narrative: This was my first impression of TeePee Curios in Tucumcari when I visited on my birthday in 2019. I had driven through Texas when I ran into a nasty storm, which led the way to an enchanted evening in New Mexico, giving me quite the dramatic sky behind the neon. I eventually went in TeePee Curios with my grandma in 2022 and bought a souvenir from there.

Name: 66 Diner
Narrative: To visit 66 Diner in Albuquerque is to step back in time to the 1950s. Malts, shakes, and burgers fuel the menu while a jukebox and an impressive collection of memorabilia create a nostalgic atmosphere. A portion of the dining room was a mechanic bay for a Phillip's gas station and service garage (there is a hydraulic lift under the hopscotch court) until it was converted into a restaurant in 1987.

Name: 66 Diner
Narrative: As the Mother Road winds through Albuquerque, it transforms into Central Avenue, where you'll find the Route 66 Diner. Before dishing out 50s-style comfort food, this streamlined modern building served as a Phillips 66 gas station. The eclectic decor features vintage neon signs, a soda fountain, a Route 66 wall map, a jukebox, and even a Pez collection. Outside, a wall displays a collection of vintage Route 66 road and business signs.

Name: Dog House Drive-In
Narrative: An institution of Route 66 in Albuquerque, the Dog House Drive-In is a favorite of locals and visitors. The iconic and humorous neon sign of a dachshund chewing a string of sausages has been featured in pop culture ("Breaking Bad") and has been a beacon for hungry travelers for decades. Name: Casa de Suenos Old Town Historic Inn
Casas de Suenos Old Town Historic Inn, Ascend Hotel Collection
Narrative: A few years back I did  Rt 66 trip. There are many fond memories of the historic wonders along the way. The Highlight of the trip was Old Town Albuquerque,  but more specifically Casas de Suenos Historic B&B. While much of Rt 66 is barely hanging on, Old Town Albuquerque is more vibrant with various eateries and a great walkable Old Town environment. Casas de Suenos is an absolutely wonderful assemblage of studio to 2BR Casitas set in a beautiful garden setting. Originally built approx 1930s as an artist enclave, it is a wonderful National Historic Register property that deserves a visit even if time or availability doesn't allow a stay over. I will absolutely make it a point to stop through again any time my travels take me through or close to Albuquerque.

Name: El Morro Theatre
Narrative: Route 66 has many beautiful old movie theatres, and El Morro is on the top of my list of favorite places.  I've had the pleasure of showing my historic women's history documentaries here, including The Harvey Girls: Opportunity Bound and Route 66: The Untold Story of Women on the Mother Road.  The 1928 theatre is the only example of Spanish Colonial Revival architecture in Gallup. It was designed by Carl Boller of the Boller Brothers architecture firm of Los Angeles and Kansas City. The Boller Brothers firm was responsible for designing many theaters in the Southwest, Midwest and California. Once described as a "castle of pleasure and art", the El Morro occupies a prominent location on Coal Avenue and has been the backdrop to many Indian Tribal Ceremonial parades.  Featured in this photo is Harvey Girl Virginia Tellez Wayne and her son Michael.  Virgina worked at the El Navajo Harvey House in Gallup, New Mexico and at many other Route 66 restaurants.

Name: Odeon Theatre: Prep to paint the Odeon Theatre
Pops 66
Image_Cr: Carol M. Highsmith, Library of Congress

Name: House of Clay
Tags: Shopping; Arts, Culture & Entertainment; Sights & Activities

Name: Cherokee Nation Anna Mitchell Cultural & Welcome Center
Bristow Train Depot and Museum
Narrative: Turning 100 years old in 2024, the FRISCO Train Depot in historic downtown Bristow, Oklahoma is home to an all-volunteer community museum which has garnered state and national notice. Visitors stepping into the historically accurate lobby will be transported to former waiting rooms where they can view carefully curated exhibits, grouped topically, sharing the history of early Bristow and Oklahoma: the dirt road that would later become Route 66, the foot racers of the 1928 Bunion Derby, the days of hidden moonshine, the starkness of segregation, and train departures of our hometown military members during World War I, Korea, and continuing through Vietnam. Families will love the caboose outside and depot plaza with picnic tables and plenty of room for the kids to run. We share our history so that we can learn from the lessons of the past. Our volunteers love our hometown, and we hope you will too.
Narrative_Src: Share Your Story: Bristow Historical Society and Depot

Name: Sooner Printing & Office Supplies: Facade Restoration
Stutts House Of Barbecue
Narrative: Offering smoked ribs, beef, bologna, and chicken with all the trimmings, Stutt's House of Barbeque is a local legend in Tulsa, Oklahoma. Like so many other Route 66 businesses, it struggled to survive the COVID years, only to recently face the challenge of updating an obsolete grease fire protection exhaust system. Fortunately, its owner, Almead Stutt, learned of the Route 66 Road Ahead Partnership's Route 66 Extraordinary Women Micro-Grant Program, applied, and received a grant award in 2023 to help replace her exhaust system. As a recent customer noted, Absolutely amazing. My son and I stopped in today and we were not disappointed. When you pull up you can smell the delicious bbq and then when you walk in you feel right at home and comfortable almost like you're walking into Grandma's house.

Name: J.M. Davis Arms & Historical Museum
Image_Cr: Steven H. Roemerman, Sr., Wikimedia Commons

Name: Wanda J's Next Generation Soul Food Restaurant
Hi-Way Cafe
Narrative: In 2022, the Hi-Way Cafe in Vinita, Oklahoma was awarded the Guiness World Record for Most Stickers on a Car. Look closely - there are over 60,000 tiny stickers covering this AMC Rambler!

Name: Hi-Way Cafe
Narrative: Built in 1963 by Tom Schwartz the cafe is located 2 miles west of Vinita, OK on Route 66.  Purchased 13 years ago by the Wood/Hilburn families the cafe has focused on putting their cafe on the radar for roadies as a roadside attraction.  Successfully awarded a Guinness Book of World Record for the "Most Stickers on a Car', the 1963 AMC Rambler is parked inside the cafe for guests to dine with the car.  The cafe is the current home of two massive fiberglass giants.  A 21-foot fiberglass giant, "Big Bill" and his 23-foot fiberglass giant friend, "The Big Indian".  Looking further around the property you will find a Lil' Big Boy, Betty Boop and another 1963 AMC Rambler placed outside for guests to use a sticker to "sticker" the car for a selfie.  Amazing homestyle food, friendly staff and fun atmosphere this is a stop you don't want to miss! Known for their burgers, chicken fried steaks, monthly steak nights and homemade onion rings and ranch dressing.  It's like stepping back in time!

Name: Lucille's Roadhouse and Hotel
Image_Cr: Digital Photographs Relating to America's Byways, National Archives

Name: Tally's Good Food Cafe
Narrative: Another fun place for food on the Mother Road is Tally's Cafe.  When we began our journey in Funks Grove, Illinois, we met a couple of fellow travelers at the Maple Sirup shop, had a nice conversation and wished them well on their trip. So, some time later, we are sitting in Tally's and who do we see also having lunch?  You guessed it!  It's a small world on Route 66!
Narrative_Src: Share Your Story: R Dean Larson

Name: Dairy King
Image_Cr: Carol M. Highsmith, Library of Congress

Name: The Dairy King of Commerce
Narrative: Charles Duboise and his mother, Treva, have operated the Dairy King since 1980 but the former gas station dates back to the 1920s. Charles is a local history expert so if you stop in for a burger or some cookies, prepare for an education!

Name: Dairy King
Narrative: Eat surrounded by the spirits of American legends at the Dairy King restaurant. Located in the northeast corner of Oklahoma, the structure originally operated as a Marathon gas station, opening shortly after Route 66 arrived in town in 1926. Retro gas pumps remind us of the adorable red and white building's original function. However, the Mother Road is not the only famous presence in Commerce. Bonnie and Clyde made an infamous visit in 1934, and Mickey Mantle's childhood home is just a few blocks away. The Dairy King is a hallmark of Americana in Commerce. Ice cream was first sold on site in the 1950s, and the Dairy King?s soft serve still beckons Route 66 travelers and local residents. The restaurant, owned and operated in its current form by Treva and Charles Duboise, is also known for its burgers and Route 66 cookies, shaped and decorated in the form of the Route 66 shield.

Name: Briley's Silverscreen Ice Cream, Soda & Gifts
Narrative: Located next to the Historic Coleman Theatre, Briley's offers the best ice cream in the area, unique one of a kind drinks, and a cool, relaxed 50's vibe atmosphere. Decorated with movie posters and memorabilia, stepping into this shop will take you back to the good 'ol days.

Name: Ed Galloway's Totem Pole Park
Image_Cr: Carol M. Highsmith, Library of Congress

Name: Texas Theater
Image_Cr: James R. Powell Postcard Collection, Newberry Library, Wikimedia Commons

Name: Texas Ivy Antiques
Narrative: Texas Ivy Antiques is a family owned business founded in 1997 on Route 66 by Florence Mildred Carroll. Our antique & Route 66 gift shop is housed in a 1921 one story wood frame structure, one of the original homes in our San Jacinto Heights Neighborhood. In August of 2022 Texas Ivy Antiques had a devastating fire, however thanks to all of our wonderful supporters we were able to reopen in June of 2023. We are looking forward to another 27 years on TEXAS 66!Texas Ivy Antiques is home to the Famous TEXAS 66 Sign where hundreds of tourists and travels have their picture taken each year. NEW in 2024 is our Route 66 Roadside Attraction Sign for another photo opportunity!Texas Ivy Antiques has Route 66 and local area attraction travel information to share and is a Stamping location for the 8 State MOTHER ROAD ROUTE 66 PASSPORT.

Name: The Big Texan Steak Ranch
Image_Cr: Carol M. Highsmith, Library of Congress

Name: The Big Texan
Narrative: The Big Texan isn't just a restaurant, it's an experience. Where else can you get a free 72 oz steak for free if you eat it (and all the fixin's) in an hour?

Name: The Big Texan Steak Ranch & Brewery
Narrative: Driving with two friends from New York City to California in June 1966, in a brand new 1966 Volkswagen beetle, we picked up Route 66 in St. Louis. One of the many memorable stops along the way was Amarillo, Texas, home of the original Big Texan, which opened on Amarillo Blvd. (aka Route 66) in 1960. The cowboy-costumed greeter handed me this postcard and said, "If you can find my horse in this picture you can eat for free." I said it was the Chevy parked behind him. I was right. My friends--one of whom was my future husband--had to pay for their steaks.
Narrative_Src: Share Your Story: Helen A. Harrison

Name: The Big Texan Steak Ranch: The Big Texan Cowboy Sign Restoration Phase 1
Import Corner
Historic_Name: Experimental military building at Kingman Airfield
Narrative: Just off Route 66, Import Corner operates from a World War II–era experimental military building at the historic Kingman Airfield — a structure built for secrecy, not showrooms. While it likely never housed a B-52, its thick walls and isolated design suggest it stored something important — maybe even classified. Today, that same building bursts with life, color, and culture. Inside, you'll find handcrafted goods from over 50 countries — mosaic lamps, ceramics, and décor that carry stories from across the globe. We’ve taken a piece of wartime infrastructure and transformed it into a cultural hub that honors the past while embracing the future. Route 66 once moved troops, families, and dreamers across the nation. Now, it brings travelers to our doorstep, where history meets handmade. Import Corner isn’t just a stop — it’s a living chapter in Kingman’s Route 66 story. We're not preserving the past — we’re lighting it up, one artisan piece at a time.

Name: Old Crater Trading Post
Narrative: In 1936 Claude and Willa Bowlin opened the Old Crater Trading Post, named for the nearby ancient volcanic crater, was a two story building that ran parallel to unpaved Route 66, and located about a mile north of Bluewater, New Mexico. Constructed of wooden slab, the building housed the store and living quarters. The upstairs level had a porch across the front that provided shade to the store entrance below. Claude draped large colorful rugs over the railings to showcase the handiwork of the local Navajo women; their lovely, simple patterns fluttering in the seemingly ceaseless wind. The building no longer exists, but Bowlin Travel Centers, Inc. still operates a store in Bluewater today.

Name: Reeves Filling Station
Narrative: In the wide plains of the Texas Panhandle, just east of Amarillo, a quiet stucco building stands against the sky—the last witness to a town that time forgot. Built in 1911 by Phil Reeves, the Reeves Filling Station served early Route 66 travelers braving the infamous Jericho Gap, where deep ruts and muddy roads often left drivers stranded.Jericho, Texas was once a lively stop along the Mother Road, but like so many towns bypassed by progress, it faded after Route 66 was rerouted. As homes crumbled, the Reeves Filling Station endured, a reminder of a time when grit and community made all the difference crossing the Panhandle.Today, thanks to the Preserve Route 66 Legacy Business Grant, we are stabilizing and restoring this important landmark. Saving the Reeves Filling Station is about more than preserving stucco walls—it’s about honoring the travelers, dreamers, and hard-working families who helped shape the spirit of Route 66.

Name: The Original Location of Mel-O-Cream Donuts
Narrative: At the height of the Great Depression Kelly Grant Sr. opened a donut shop in Springfield, Illinois. With the support of the local community and Grant family leadership, the business grew into multiple retail stores and a thriving wholesale business. Today, Mel-O-Cream Donuts International ships wholesale donuts across the United States. The retail donut shop tradition continues with five Mel-O-Cream stores in Springfield, IL and one in Lincoln, IL. We invite you to stop in and share the delicious history with over 30 different types of donuts that are made daily.

Name: Buzz Bomb Brewing Co
Status_Note: Modern building
Narrative: We are Buzz Bomb Brewing Co located in downtown Springfield, IL - just off the legendary Route 66! We're proud supporters and members of the IL Route 66 Scenic Byway and our building hosts a mural for the Route 66 Monarch Flyway. Cheers!

Name: Mother Road Brewing Company
Narrative: Route 66 is a highway steeped in history, culture, and the endless possibilities of the open road.  When completed, it gave motorists unparalleled freedom to roam and connected small towns and big cities in never-before-seen-ways. Author John Steinbeck gave Route 66 the moniker, 'the mother road' in his classic novel The Grapes of Wrath.  The highway was a road to opportunity for people seeking a better life.Running through our hometown of Flagstaff, Arizona, Route 66 still holds a powerful place in our culture.  We've imbued its adventurousness and innovative spirit into the foundations of everything we build, do, and brew.

Name: Weatherford Wind Energy Center
Narrative: Weatherford, Oklahoma celebrates their local energy community with a colorful mural on a wind turbine blade outside of City Hall. A smaller-scale replica of the Vietnam Memorial wall can be seen in the background.

Name: Fish Bowl Spring
Narrative: Fish Bowl Spring is a small, fresh water spring near Oatman, Arizona that locals keep stocked with goldfish. It sits along a winding stretch of Route 66 in the Black Mountains.

Name: Bottle Tree Ranch
Narrative: Bottle Tree Ranch is a passion project from the late Elmer Long and a popular roadside attraction in California.

Name: Baxter Springs' marsh arch bridge
Narrative: A group of drag-and-drive race participants pause for photos at Baxter Springs' marsh arch bridge, the only one of its kind left on Historic Route 66.

Name: Rainbow Bridge
Narrative: Rainbow Bridge, located in Cherokee County Kansas, on the 13.2 miles of Kansas Historic Route 66 and the only Marsh Arch Bridge along the entire Route. You can still drive across the bridge and if you lucky you might meet Dean " Crazy Legs Walker" ( Oh yeah, that's another story) out there making sure there is no one tagging the bridge. It was once called the graffiti because it looked similar to the Cadillac's in Texas all covered with graffiti.

Name: Rainbow Bridge
Narrative: One of the best vehicles for a road trip? A Jeep! I was heading home from a weekend with friends and I always made it a goal to take the scenic route instead of the interstate. When opportunity knocks to take your Jeep or other cool car through one of the only rainbow bridges left, take it!

Name: William H. Murray Bridge
Narrative: The William H. Murray Bridge in Central Oklahoma, popularly known as the Pony Bridge, is one of the longest bridges on Route 66. It was completely rebuilt in 2024 with the original trusses re-attached to a new deck.

Name: Soulsby's Service Station
Narrative: Soulsby's Service Station in Mount Olive, Illinois no longer dispenses gasoline but it's a wonderful time capsule to the past.

Name: Illinois Capitol
Narrative: Springfield, Illinois' Capitol building is one of three that have been part of the Route 66 corridor.

Name: CountryAire Restaurant
Narrative: Lumi the Giant is a custom Uniroyal Gal built for the Country-Aire Restaurant in Atlanta, Illinois.

Name: Gary's Gay Parita
Narrative: Gary Turner built this oasis in Paris Springs, Missouri as a tribute to an original Sinclair station on Route 66.

Name: Heart of Historic Route 66
Narrative: This beautifully repurposed neon sign from Las Vegas, Nevada was moved to Kingman and restored alongside Route 66.

Name: Onion Burger Historical Marker
Narrative: El Reno's onion burgers are a depression-era invention of necessity and remains a delicious pit stop along the Mother Road.

Name: Allen's Fillin' Station
Narrative: Allen's Fillin' Station, or the Hole in the Wall, is a small building built into the side of a larger one. It's a popular photo op for travelers and locals.

Name: Smith Lumber Yard
Historic_Name: Palace Drug Store, front street garage
Narrative: This ghost sign on the side of a former lumber yard and garage in Galena, Kansas was an inspiration for the art in Pixar's film, Cars.

Name: Camp Joy Cabin
Narrative: The lone remaining cabin from central Missouri's Camp Joy now has a home in the city park of Lebanon, Missouri along with a replica archway.

Name: Johnson Creek Bridge
Narrative: This truss bridge in Spencer, Missouri is one of the few remaining historic truss bridges on Route 66.

Name: Westfall Phillips 66 Station
Narrative: This original Phillips 66 station has been partially restored and serves as seating for a nearby food truck today.

Name: Historic McLean Water Tower
Narrative: The McLean water tower was built in 1934-35 as a Public Works Administration (PWA) project. For nearly the entire history of Route 66, travelers have seen the tower from afar, a sign that they are nearing the Village of McLean. In 2017, a new, larger tower was erected to meet increased water demand. The original water tower was decommissioned and emptied but remains in its original location. Nonprofit group CORE of McLean has turned the property below into a park, which is now part of the Route 66 Monarch flyway as it is home to a thriving garden of native and pollinator-friendly plants. In 2023-24, CORE conducted a successful campaign to save the water tower from demolition and are planning restoration of the tower in 2025. This restoration project is funded in part by grant funds from the Preserve Route 66 Grant Fund of the National Trust for Historic Preservation and the Landmarks Illinois Preservation Heritage Fund Grant Program as well as donations from supporters.

Name: Downtown Service Station
Narrative: Downtown Service Station Route 66's last bonafide full-service stop in Missouri By Laura Abernathy Huffman Ding! Ding! When you roll across the rubber hose that alerts the attendants at Downtown Service Station you are transported to the forgotten era of full-service gasoline stations. The Sharadin family's downtown business in Waynesville is the last of its kind in the Show-Me-State. It is the only remaining full-service gasoline service station left on Route 66 in Missouri, possibly the only one still in operation on the entire iconic Mother Road between Chicago and the Santa Monica Pier in California. The station is bonafide Route 66. It was opened on the corner of Olive Street in 1972, by Paul Shultz, when Route 66 was still America's main street.

Name: Downtown Service Station restoration to Historic Route 66 grandeur...
The Mitla Cafe - San Bernardino, CA
Narrative: This film still shows the Mitla Cafe in San Bernardino. Founded by Lucía Rodríguez in the 1930s, it is still run by her family today. Lucía's husband Salvador worked for the railroad, as did many Mexican-American men, and the West side of the city was flourishing. Mount Vernon Avenue was a natural stopping point for Route 66 travelers after the barren desert. Lucía, who was the matriarch of her family, used her teenage daughters' help to run the new family business 24-hours a day. Although strict, Lucía's efforts paid off and the business was a hit! Glen Bell had a hot dog stand across the street from the Mitla Cafe and observed how well it was doing. So well, in fact, that he took it upon himself to learn how to make tacos from Lucía and Salvador before launching Taco Bell. The Mitla Cafe is now in the hands of the third generation and it is still a necessary stop for every politician who wants any clout in San Bernardino.

Name: Buck Atom's Cosmic Curios
Narrative: We were in the Pearl District of Tulsa, OK and stopped at Buck Atom's Cosmic Curios on 66. Soon, an historic car pulled up all decked out in our beautiful American flag design! It fit so well there I had to snap the photo. Talked with the car owner and he is a big Route 66 fan. Felt lucky to be there at the right time.

Name: Pine Breeze Inn
Narrative: Pine Breeze Inn in Bellemont, west of Flagstaff, includes rustic cabins and a former Richfield filling station. The Pine Breeze, more than 75 years old, had a cameo in the opening of 'Easy Rider' when Wyatt and Billy rode up at dusk on their noisy choppers. A frightened Pine Breeze motel clerk ducks inside to turn on the No Vacancy sign. That prompts the bikers to roar off into the darkness on this abandoned two-mile stretch of Route 66.

Name: Camp Cajon Monument
Narrative: The original Camp Cajon Monument was dedicated on July 4, 1919 along the National Old Trails Road which was later became Route 66 in 1926. Camp Cajon was a popular rest stop and picnic area for travelers. It was built by William Bristol as the gateway to Southern California. Local organizations built other structures at the Camp and contributed round cement picnic tables with the donor organization's name inscribed on a brass plaque. Sadly, the Camp was destroyed by a huge flood in 1938. Today volunteers have reconstructed the monument and added interpretive signage about the trails that passed through this area.  An original picnic table was recently added.  The monument is located on Interstate 15 (with Route 66 buried underneath). Drive past the McDonald's at Wagon Trail Road. There is a Route 66 shield painted in the roadway. It's a good place to take a photo as there is not much traffic on that dead end road.
Narrative_Src: Share Your Story: Tom and Lynne Miller

Name: Camp Cajon Monument
Narrative: Camp Cajon was built on National Old Trails Road in 1919 to serve the newly motorized American public. National Old Trails Road became U.S. Route 66 in 1926, and Camp Cajon became famous as The Gateway to Southern California. The camp was badly damaged by a flood in 1938, and was removed in 1939 when Route 66 was widened. Nearly forgotten, the Camp Cajon historic site was brought back to life in 2019 by a group of volunteers led by the San Bernardino Historical & Pioneer Society. The volunteers built a large stone replica of the camp?s original entrance monument that was dedicated on July 4, 2019, celebrating the 100-year anniversary of the camp's founding. The site now features several historic relics including a 1917 monument, the 2019 Camp Cajon Monument, an original Camp Cajon picnic table, and an informational kiosk. The present-day site of Camp Cajon is located at 3355 Wagon Train Road (formerly Route 66), just east of Interstate 15, and south of Highway 138, in the Cajon Pass.

Name: End of the Trail
Narrative: Located on the Santa Monica pier in southern California, this sign marks the end of Route 66.  What a great trip!
Narrative_Src: Share Your Story: R. Dean Larson

Name: End of the Trail
Narrative: The intrigue of Route 66 lures many to find the open roads. With the promise of adventure, and after 25 years of casual talk about 'someday we should do that' it finally happened. Two wild Rosie's jumped in an older classic Buick, consulting some cheeky little maps we headed off to explore. We had a short window to accomplish our trip. I guess from the beginning our main goal was just to get out there, drive, see what we could see, and make an amazing finish. And what a better finish than the  demonstration of a current trend of the times, a selfie in front of the End of the Trail  sign. Our photographic documentation of our accomplishment of conquering our own little part of Route 66.Each encounter and every experience has its own story and as you travel along, you realize the journey becomes your own personalized memory.

Name: U. S. Post Office Route 66
Narrative: This is the cutest little post office ever!  Not only is it the Topock Post Office, but it is also the headquarters of the Topock Art Guild.  Such a multipurpose location!
Narrative_Src: Share Your Story: R. Dean Larson

Name: Burma Shave signs
Narrative: These are the classic Burma Shave advertising signs that use to be seen on all the long drives people would take.  These are just outside Seligman, AZ, on the way to Kingman.
Narrative_Src: Share Your Story: R. Dean Larson

Name: Aztec Motel
Narrative: A charming motel that really embraces the Route 66 theme!
Narrative_Src: Share Your Story: R. Dean Larson

Name: Painted Desert Visitor Center
Narrative: The Painted Desert is a landscape of badlands that extend some 150 miles from the eastern end of the Grand Canyon into Petrified National Forest.  The name Painted Desert refers to the rainbow of colorful sedimentary layers exposed in the austere landscape.  It is an amazingly beautiful place to visit - both colorfully and spiritually.
Narrative_Src: Share Your Story: R. Dean Larson

Name: Blake's Lotaburger
Narrative: Some unexpected architecture in New Mexico!
Narrative_Src: Share Your Story: R. Dean Larson

Name: El Sendero Inn
Narrative: Garrett's Inn (currently named El Sendero Inn) is located on the Old Santa Fe Trail just down the street from the San Miguel Chapel.  It is a mid-century motel that is comfortable and reasonably priced.
Narrative_Src: Share Your Story: R. Dean Larson

Name: San Miguel Chapel
Narrative: One of the oldest adobe church in Santa Fe.  Built in the 17th Century, it is still active today and holds restored paintings and other artifacts.
Narrative_Src: Share Your Story: R. Dean Larson

Name: Main Street,  Route 66
Narrative: As we pulled onto Main Street in Hydro, Oklahoma, we were stunned at how empty it was!  It was a bit disconcerting as we rolled down the empty street.  Turning a corner, we saw a church parking lot that was packed with cars, and that was when we realized it was a Sunday and everyone was either in church or at home!  What a relief!
Narrative_Src: Share Your Story: R. Dean Larson

Name: Pops 66 Cafe sculpture
Narrative: Iconic landmark on Route 66 featuring a 66 ft tall soda bottle sculpture, diner, gas station with half a dozen pumps, and an extensive selection of glass bottled soda!  The food looks delicious, and seriously, they have every bottle of soda that can be imagined!
Narrative_Src: Share Your Story: R. Dean Larson

Name: Lucilles Gas Station
Narrative: An iconic stop on Route 66, it was one of the earlier gas stations available to travelers.  Located a half-mile south of Hydro, Oklahoma and operated by Lucille Hamons from 1941 until her death on August 18, 2000, the site was added to the US National Register of Historic Places in 1997.
Narrative_Src: Share Your Story: R. Dean Larson

Name: Skyliner Motel
Narrative: Here is another iconic bit of signage from Route 66  -  The Skyliner Motel.  Just the right blend of modern and neon.  Definitely eye catching.
Narrative_Src: Share Your Story: R Dean Larson

Name: Route 66 Rocker
Narrative: Just outside of Cuba, MO is one of the iconic Route 66 stops --  The Worlds Largest Rocker!  Couldn't pass up stopping for a photo!
Narrative_Src: Share Your Story: R Dean Larson

Name: Ambler's Texaco Gas Station
Narrative: First stop on our Rt 66 trip was in Dwight, Il to get a quick bite to eat.  Drove past this restored Texaco Gas Station and had to stop for a photo!

Name: Ambler's Texaco Gas Station
Narrative: How often does one see a Route 66 landmark in snow? I was walking to work (only about half a mile away from my house) and I had the opportunity to take this photo of the Ambler-Becker Texaco Station during snowfall. It belongs in a snow globe, don't you think?

Name: Ambler's Texaco Gas Station
Narrative: I was raised in the small town of Dwight, IL in a house just one block away from Route 66. The Ambler-Becker Texaco Station was a two-block walk and I spent one summer volunteering on Sundays for two hours. I marveled at all the amazing cars that came through, like this one, and I was in awe at how many people travel to this town, my hometown, from all around the world to travel Route 66. I also enjoyed making suggestions to the other landmarks for tourists to explore in Dwight because I grew up with them. Because of this, Dwight will always have a place in my heart.

Name: Funks Grove Country Store
Narrative: Before we started our Rt 66 journey, we had heard of a great place to get real Maple "Sirup" in Funks Grove.  On the way, we turned onto a side road and came across this country store.  It wasn't open then, but I had to take a photo -- don't want to forget this place!
Narrative_Src: Share Your Story: R. Dean Larson

Name: Locomotive Park
Narrative: When we were kids in the 60s our parents took us on Route 66 and I fell in love with this train in Kingman, Arizona that the two lane road went around. After my 55th Newport Harbor High School reunion in 2022 I drove it back to Nashville and while the town has grown the train is still there.  Wonderful memory!

Name: Spragues Super Service
Narrative: Located at 305 Pine Street in Normal, Sprague Super Service was built in the early 1930's . It originally had a gas station, garage, and restaurant as well as an apartment upstairs for the owner and garage attendant. The site is the only Tudor revival gas station on Route 66, an is on the National Register of Historic Places and Illinois Route 66 Hall of Fame. Ryburn's Place at Sprague's Super Service is open 9-5, Wednesday through Sunday. Information Center and Gift Shop

Name: Sandhill Curiosity Shop
Narrative: Our organization 66ForThe22 just rode the entire length of Route 66, to raise money and awareness for Veteran Suicide, mental health and PTSD. This is part of the group at the Sandhills Curiosity Shop in Erick, OK.

Name: Downtown Flagstaff
Narrative: On a wintry day in February 1996, we pulled in behind this pickup parked outside a curio shop on East Route 66, Flagstaff?s main street. The katsina carver or vendor was inside negotiating with the shop?s proprietor ahead of the coming tourist season. Meanwhile, outside, his odd  passengers huddled expectantly in the truck bed without audible complaint.

Name: Route 66 Museum
Narrative: In 2016, we took our Cocker Spaniel, Andy, with us on a 3 week road trip from Mississippi to west coast and back. Carey got a cool shirt at Route 66 Museum in Kingman, AZ.
Narrative_Src: Share Your Story: Sharon Gibbons Varnado

Name: Gillioz Theatre
Narrative: This historic theatre was built in 1926 by regional bridge builder M.E. Gillioz. Established on the newly announced Route 66, the theatre was originally a hybrid theatre; hosting both vaudeville and film presentations. As vaudeville faded, the theatre leaned more heavily on film programming, and eventually closed. A passionate community rallied to see the Gillioz restored and reopened in 2006.The Gillioz has emerged as the premiere event venue in Springfield. Programming includes a blend of film, music concerts, conferences, comedy, theatre, and opera. The ornate décor is breathtaking, and the intimacy of the 1044-seat theatre makes every presentation historic for both patron and performer.

Name: historic turner manufacturing company
Narrative: In the summers of the mid 1960s, I rode the CTA to join the 500 people working at Turner Manufacturing Company making framed pictures, fine and popular art, Rembrandts and Picassos, silkscreen flamingos, swirly cityscapes, Keene Big Eyes and religious studies. The men and women were southwest Chicago: Polish, Czech, German, Irish, Italian, Black, White, Hispanic. One year I was in payroll sorting timecards, the next on the factory floor hauling skipjacks of frames, paper, glass, and product from work line to elevators, elevators to work line. At the corner tavern I fetched lunches for 35¢, 45¢ with fries. We set up a new plastic machine to mold amazing repros of grand baroque picture frames. Another time I followed the paintmaster Wally Prezwoznik visiting the factories with whose paint Turner made magic, learning how to apply a delicate finish. It was hot & humid, there were salt pill dispensers in the toilets, it was one of the factories that made Chicago great & grand.

Name: Turner Manufacturing Company
Narrative: Some fifth generation Turners stand in front of The Turner Manufacturing Company on Ogden and Keeler in Lawndale where four generations of Turners worked alongside 500+ employees creating picture frames, furniture, mirrors and art. Built in 1918 by August Turner with Chicago architect Alfred Alschuler on the historic Route 66, this classic red-brick factory is now threatened with demolition to turn it into a toxic truck depot. The Ogden-Keeler buildings symbolize the Chicago history of immigrants, the lumber industry, wood craftsmanship and fine art. Check out the pop-art silkscreen favorite, The Turner Flamingoes in mirrored Turner frames! Not only do these buildings represent immigrant labor and a Chicago success story, they also signal a positive future if the buildings are repurposed to best serve Lawndale with new opportunities.
Narrative_Src: Share Your Story: Susan Turner Jones

Name: Crown Candy Kitchen
Narrative: Since 1913, Crown Candy Kitchen has been serving Route 66 travelers and local St. Louis residents sweet treats. The business was founded by Greek immigrants Harry Karandzieff and Pete Jugaloff  who possessed unique confectionary skills. Throughout the decades as the business continued to grow more sweet and savory treats were added to the menu and now Crown Candy Kitchen is known as the oldest soda fountain in St. Louis. Today, Crown Candy Kitchen is operated by the 3rd and 4th generations of the Karandzieff family.

Name: 1912 Market on 66
Narrative: The 1912 Market on 66 is a valued outlet for locally grown and processed food products in western New Mexico. Established in 2020 by Bobbie and Kevin Branum, the market aims to address rural New Mexico's food access issues, disproportionately affecting Indigenous communities, which were intensified by pandemic-era disruptions. Connecting regional producers and processors with area residents and Route 66 travelers, the market offers a selection of seasonal, fresh produce; locally raised and processed beef; year-round products, such as tortillas and dairy; and natural beauty and wellness products. The 1912 Market has partnered with fellow local business Mt. Taylor Coffee to provide your roadside caffeine fix at their location directly on historic Route 66.

Name: Polk's House
Narrative: The pocket-sized Polk's House restaurant stands proudly on the corner of NE 23rd Street and Lottie Avenue in Oklahoma City, just a few blocks from the Oklahoma State Capitol. This take-out operation was opened in 2015 by chefs James and Shacopie Polk. The husband-and-wife team serves up a range of Southern-style to-go dishes, including Cajun and soul favorites. Crab boils, chicken and waffles, meatloaf, and pasta, among others, feature on the menu. This restaurant in Oklahoma City's East End was once the Pink Kitchen Cafe. Operating segregated lunch counters, the Pink Kitchen was the site of a Civil Rights Movement sit-in that ended in the unjust arrest of activist Clara Luper. The current owners pay respect to this important moment in civil rights history, displaying a newspaper clipping from the 1961 event at Polk's House.

Name: Mother Road Market
Narrative: The Mother Road Market is an exciting new addition to the Route 66 story and a dedicated Tulsa community partner. The food hall concept, opened in 2018 as a program of the Lobeck Taylor Family Foundation, offers an extensive variety of cuisines, from street tacos to Jewish deli sandwiches and Cajun classics to Brazilian bites. Overall, more than 20 business concepts operate on the site.However, this nonprofit food hall is concerned with more than gastronomic discovery. The Mother Road Market's Kitchen 66 is dedicated to offering developmental support for Tulsa's food entrepreneurs via a number of programs, including business training, affordable commercial kitchen access, and sales opportunities. The market's community presence and popularity has not gone unnoticed; USA Today has proclaimed it the Best Food Hall nationwide for the second year in a row (2023 and 2024).

Name: Garcia's Kitchen
Narrative: Garcia's Kitchen is a familiar face in Albuquerque. Originally opened by Andy Garcia in 1975, the business currently operates half a dozen locations in the Albuquerque area. Locals and Route 66 travelers have frequented the restaurant for generations for its classic Mexican and New Mexican cuisine, including menudo, carne adovada, and sopapillas. Early risers benefit from an expansive breakfast menu, while those looking to bring home a taste of New Mexico can purchase a bottle of Garcia's red or green chile for takeaway. The business's location at 1736 Central Ave. SW is shown above. Sitting directly on historic Route 66, this location is notable for its bounteous signage. Multiple vintage (and newer) signs depict Andy Garcia's sombrero-clad persona, drawing ever-more visitors to the cafe bearing his name long after ownership has passed to the family's younger generation. Follow this vintage sign's bright yellow arrow for a long-running purveyor of regional favorites.

Name: Rest Haven Motel
Narrative: They have painted over the Billss Paid now, But this always was my most favorite sign on the Route.  Always wondered what Billss they paid?   In Afton OK

Name: Seligman Garage
Narrative: The Seligman Garage was a beacon to Route 66 travelers coming through Arizona. Thomas Cook and Guy Sykes owned the garage for many years where they stayed busy repairing cars and selling Studebakers. Just as important, the garage was also known as the host of the annual Seligman Rodeo dance. On that summer evening, Tom would sweep under the canopy and pews from a local church were brought in to line the perimeter of the cement. A generous amount of sawdust was sprinkled on the dance floor so that those cowboy boots would slide properly on the floor. The Black Cat Bar was just across the street, so a quick walk across Route 66 could quench your thirst. Imagine driving along Route 66 on that summer evening. As you approached, you first heard music, then you saw cowboys and cowgirls having the time of their lives dancing the night away under the canopy of the Seligman Garage. The building is still there, although no longer a garage, and it lives on in the history of the Mother Road.

Name: Santa Domingo Trading Post
Narrative: I came across this trading post as I was exploring the early alignment of Route 66 up through Santa Fe, New Mexico in 2023.  The trading post seemed to be closed, and the extension of this trading post building to the left of what is shown in this photo is in pretty bad shape. The roof is missing and many of the windows were broken. I wish I knew more about what was in store for the future of this building as it seems to have great potential.

Name: Santo Domingo Trading Post
Narrative: As Route 66 approached the Navajo, Hopi, Zuni, and Pueblo reservations of northern New Mexico and Arizona, trading posts drew travelers' interest. Their location along this major highway gave these businesses access to the passing motorists as well as nearby Native communities. Old-time traders had one foot in each world. Many still bartered packaged food goods and supplies directly with the Native Americans in exchange for traditional crafts such as weavings, jewelry, or pottery, which in turn could be offered to the tourists. A view inside Mike Kirk's trading post in 1930 shows the array of goods typically available then. After operating posts far outside town for nearly 20 years, Richard Bruchman moved into Winslow in 1921 and ran his curio shop there for another 50 years. (We found his original letterhead printing block at a flea market in Missouri a while back.) Gilbert Ortega established his many specialty shops throughout the region later in the 20th century.

Name: 2nd Amendment Cowboy
Narrative: 'Texas is a state of mind. Texas is an obsession. Above all, Texas is a nation in every sense of the word' - Author John Steinbeck. I thought this image reflected the character of west Texas outside of Amarillo.

Name: Garland Prairie Vista
Narrative: About 20 miles west of Flagstaff, Route 66 pilgrims can take exit 178 past Bellemont to visit an inspiring 1930s alignment that passes through Parks, Arizona and the Kaibab National Forest. The highlight here is a half-mile length paved in original concrete. Near the end of that length, on the south side, is a 1939 rest stop called Garland Prairie Vista. In 2004, my fiance and I indulged our mutual love of Route 66 by driving it "from Chicago to L.A." Among our cherished memories of the trip is that remarkably preserved concrete. Standing there in the silent forest with the San Francisco Peaks as a backdrop, we shared a reverent moment. We felt as though we were channeling the hopes, dreams and spirits of all who had passed that way before us. So impressed were we with this part of the road that we chose to get married on it in 2006. Many of our friends relaxed in the classic rest stop while sharing our destination/theme wedding with us in the tranquility of the Mother Road.

Name: Enchanted Trails RV Park & Trading Post
Narrative: I love that the Enchanted Trails RV Park & Trading Post in Albuquerque has a mini-museum of restored vintage trailers! I think this one may have been my favorite (a vintage 1954 VaKaShunette trailer named "Evelyn" pulled by a 1950 Hudson Commodore.  They've got seen different trailers from the 1950s, 60s and 70s.  They're all restored inside and out, so be sure to ask the front desk about getting a key so you can check out the interiors as well!

Name: Budville Trading Post
Narrative: The unsolved murders of Howard Neal "Bud" Rice and Blanche Brown at the Budville Trading Post make this a notorious and mysterious stop along Route 66. In the tiny town of Budville (yes named for Bud), Rice was a successful businessman with deep connections to local commerce, law enforcement, and transportation services. In 1967 Bud and part-time employee Blanche were brutally murdered inside the trading post. Bud's wife Flossie continued to run the business until her death 12 years later. The double homicide was never solved and the trading post has been largely vacant since the 1980s.

Name: Ruins of Whiting Brothers Gas Station
Narrative: Once a thriving gas station chain with motels, cafes, service stations, and truck stops dotting Route 66, Whiting Brothers had closed or sold all of its nearly 100 locations by the mid-1980s. Today in San Fidel, New Mexico, the giant roadside sign is still standing as is the shell of the former filling station.

Name: Supertam on 66
Narrative: Our family orientated shop features Superman memorabilia that was collected for over 30 years on display here at SuperTam! We also carry the great Chocolate Shoppe Ice Cream, the best ice cream on Route 66!

Name: Mickey Mantle's boyhood home
Narrative: Just a couple blocks off the Mother Road as you enter Oklahoma heading west is The Mick's boyhood home. The sign tells the story of how he became the best switch-hitter in baseball history and you can walk around the grounds where he honed his hitting ability. A very cool stop, if it is still there.

Name: Tom & Suzie's Diner
Narrative: July 2016 - We stopped for lunch at Tom & Suzie's Diner after a morning of sightseeing & hiking the Petrified Forest. Mayor Bobby Tyler came up and introduced himself and gave us all city pins! We met the mayor!

Name: Claremont School of Theology
Narrative: The Claremont School of Theology spent 66 years on Foothill Blvd(rte 66) in Claremont California ...    "66 Years  on Route 66"

Name: The Mystic Santa Fe
Narrative: In the summer of 2021, my good friend Mark and I embarked on the great American road trip. Cruising across the USA in my Chevrolet, we explored the Grand Canyon, Santa Fe, Oklahoma City, and St. Louis. Part of our adventure included traveling Route 66, where we stopped to tour the Route 66 Museum in Clinton, Oklahoma. This photo captures the Silver Saddle Motel in Santa Fe at sunset. The motel from its exterior to its interior décor was a kitschy homage to a bygone era.

Name: Jones & Emmons Building
Narrative: The Jones and Emmons Building was built in 1954 and enlarged in 1958 as the home of the architects A. Quincy Jones and Frederick R. Emmons. Jones and Emmons were among the most prominent and prolific Southern California Mid Century architects, responsible for hundreds of houses, including Sunnylands, the Annenberg Estate in Rancho Mirage, and academic buildings, including the Annenberg School of Communication and Journalism at USC and Young Research Library at UCLA. Declared a City of Los Angeles Historic Cultural Monument in 2001, it is home to the architecture practice of Frederick Fisher and Partners. The building was recorded by the artist Ed Ruscha in his 1974 photographs of Los Angeles Streets. It is on a stretch of Route 66 that is now Santa Monica Boulevard, in West Los Angeles, 2.5 miles from Santa Monica Beach.

Name: Cruisin with Lincoln on 66 Visitors Center and Gift Shop
Narrative: My exhibit design firm worked closely with the McLean County Museum of History to research, develop and design 'Cruisin' With Lincoln on 66' a Route 66 and Abraham Lincoln themed Visitors Center and Gift Shop that celebrates Bloomington-Normal's rich, historical connection to both Route 66 and Abraham Lincoln through an interpretive exhibit. The Center also provides tourist assistance for travelers of today, along with many original gifts and souvenirs, often crafted by local artists and craftspeople.

Name: Rubee's Diner
Narrative: For my 50th birthday, I convinced my husband, who is a musician and spends A LOT of time travelling, to take me on a Route 66 trip to upstage the daunting milestone of turning the big 5-0. He obliged, and though we only had time for the OKC to Flagstaff portion (with side trips to Clovis, the Grand Canyon, and Phoenix), we felt immersed in the landscape, culture and history of the highway. We stayed at the Blue Swallow Motel in Tucumcari on my birthday, which was a thrill. However, since the Blue Swallow (rightfully) gets a lot of love, I am sharing a photo of Rubee's, where I had an enchilada birthday dinner.  Taken May 22, 2017

Name: United Hebrew Congregation
Narrative: This synagogue, built along what later became Route 66, has served the Jewish community of Joplin, Missouri since 1917.  The architect Austin Allen employed a Byzantine/Middle Eastern style, widely used in American synagogues at the time. The building originally had a dome and minaret. These were destroyed in a 1970 fire. Other than that, the building exterior and nearly all the sanctuary are original. The United Hebrew Congregation remains active. Our Friday Shabbat evening services are open to the public, and with enough advance notice, tours can be arranged.

Name: RockArillo 66
Narrative: The RockArillo 66 launched on 10/21/2023 and we held the after party at the Texas Route 66 Visitor Center. Myself (President of Historic 6th Street on Route 66 Association), along with my team created this new event to celebrate rock-n-roll on Route 66 to drive more visitors and promote upcoming local bands. I've met some of my favorite people and friends on Route 66. Israel Guajardo whom is a phenominal artist, I met for the first time at the center! There's so much history that's available for the tourists and visitors. You will find artwork displayed by local artists, jewelry, and modern furniture. Get your smashed Penny by Penny Clark while you visit the center! The Route 66 Festval held their after party at the center as well! I've got so many wonderful memories of the visitors, tourists, and local people that I've met at the Texas Route 66 Visitor Center.

Name: Bristow Chrysler Plymouth
Narrative: By 1949, an enterprising local businessman named Red Beard dreamed of drawing Route 66 travelers to his 24-hour automotive dealership located in Bristow, OK. With the help of local craftsmen, Red erected the tallest, independently suspended neon advertising sign in the entire southwest. His steel tower soared 102 feet tall, with a 25-foot-tall flagpole on top of that, to allow the stars and stripes to be flown high and proud.The six-foot-tall letters on the sign spelled out 'CHRYSLER PLYMOUTH' and were welded by local welders, 20 tons of steel pipe went into the construction of the tower, which is shaped like an oil derrick, true to our Oklahoma history. Our community cheered on the workers as the built and raised the tower. Sadly, the lights went dark less than a decade later when the owner died. The Bristow Historical Society is raising funds to relight this iconic piece of Route 66 history and dreams of the day when it will shine once more for travelers to enjoy. Come see us!
Narrative_Src: Share Your Story: Bristow Historical Society and Depot

Name: Grand Canyon Cafe
Narrative: As a kid in the 50?s my parents traveled from Texas to California for my Dad's job in the oil fields. Once they discovered this cafe in Flagstaff Arizona it became a destination stop for a meal. The owner in those days was Asian and my parents would strike up conversation with him about his recipes and current world events. Always a see you next time goodbye. Years later while traveling I would carry on the Grand Canyon Cafe tradition and eventually took my kids there to tell them about my memories of the place. Last time I was there in 1998, I marveled at the same green linoleum floor literally worn paper thin over the years of foot traffic. That floor immediately returned my 6 year old mind to sitting in the booth with my parents chatting with the owner. I asked to speak to the current owner to tell my story, and found myself talking to a relative of the sweet man from  my memory the 1950's.

Name: D.L. Morris Garage
Narrative: Driving back to Iowa from the national Main Street conference in Oklahoma City in May 2010, I decided to take old 66 for part of the way. Great chance to photograph vernacular roadside architecture, some of which has since disappeared. This giraffe stone garage had little left besides walls and character.

Name: Shea Historic Rt 66 Museum
Narrative: One of the first places we stopped on Route 66 in 2009 was the Shea Museum.  Bill Shea happened to be in that day, and what an interesting man!  We had a great time chatting with him and looking over all the treasures he had on display.  I see by another entry that he has passed on and things have changed a lot.  So glad we took the trip when we did.  Trip of a lifetime!
Narrative_Src: Share Your Story: Jan and Fred Hulsey

Name: Shea Historic Rt 66 Museum
Narrative: This is the former world wide recognized Shea's Route 66 Museum in Springfield Illinois.     Originally established as a Marathon Station in 1955 by Bill Shea Sr, it greatly served the north end of Springfield IL for decades and eventually morphed into a world wide known must stop Rt 66 destination. After Mr Shea's passing, it was purchased by the current owner from the original owners family in 2017, so as not to be left to deteriorate or much worse, get torn down! Progress had been slow but midway into 2023, thanks to a preservation grant, it has received a major facelift and even managed to be highlighted on the 2024 Illinois entry in the Rose Bowl parade! Be on the lookout for more great things to come as we prepare for the 100th birthday of the Mother Road!

Name: Coca Cola Mural
Narrative: The Ford Lightning made history for Ford again when it became the very first EV Truck to drive from Chicago to LA all on Route 66. This helped show the nation that you can now drive America's Mother Road and get charging all the way. This helped Ford continue its long standing as First on 66 in 1926 and now first in EV. This was an amazing trip. We stopped and got others to be encouraged to do the full route again. The trip ended at the famous Mel's Diner which is on the corner of the official end of Route 66. This was a life changing trip and making history.  This photo shows the truck stopped in front of a historic mural in Galena, Kansas.

Name: Route 66 Association of Illinois
Narrative: The museum offers a look at memorabilia and artifacts relating to Route 66, particularly in Illinois, including items relating to members of the Hall of Fame. The back outside wall of the museum offers the world's largest shield in a setting allowing visitors to capture themselves, and their rides, in pictures with the shield. As with other museums in Pontiac, admission is free. And be sure to take a look at all the beautiful murals throughout Pontiac.
Narrative_Src: Share Your Story: Dwight M Cannon

Name: Audie Murphy's Uniform at Livingston County War Museum
Narrative: The Livingston County, Illinois, War Museum and Dal Estes Education Center. A hands-on museum showcasing the uniform and medals of Audie Murphy, the most decorated soldier in WW II.  It was the only time I ever saw the Medal of Honor, never mind being able to touch one.

Name: Gemini Giant
Narrative: Our first Route 66 adventure was in 2016.  We toured from Chicago to Carthage, MO.  Unbeknownst  to us the state of Illinois was have a Route 66 festival the weekend we left from Chicago - with fun at every small town along the way in Illinois.  We covered ~800 miles over 8 days  - so much to see.  This is a picture of the Gemini Giant in Wilmington, IL.  We did the next leg of Route 66 Carthage, MO to Albuquerque, NM in 2018 and finished the final leg to Sana Monica, CA in 2020. What an adventure!  So many picture to share from each trip!

Name: Gemini Giant
Narrative: I have long romanticized the kitschy roadside attractions of Route 66. On my trip across the route, the first truly iconic one I encountered was the Gemini Giant. It seemingly appeared out of nowhere, and I swear I almost wrecked my car. This 30-foot-tall sculpture was created during the space race era and named after America's second space mission. He is a warm welcome to Wilmington and a preview of everything that will blow your mind and make you pull over as you travel the route. The pit stop next to it has an array of Gemini Giant souvenirs. I bought a bobblehead figurine of him, and he sits on my desk to remind me of the delightful weirdness that is 66.

Name: Hackberry General Store
Narrative: You could still purchase gasoline from the Hackberry General Store in 1966 when we moved to Arizona.  I drove the 1931 Model A Ford sedan from Elgin, Illinois, to Arizona in June 1966.  My husband is standing by the Ford where we stopped at Merramac Caverns in MO on that trip.

Name: Route 66, New Mexico
Narrative: We were traveling on our honeymoon in 2021. We picked up route 66 outside of Albuquerque heading west. Route 66 has been broken up by interstate 40 all across New Mexico and Arizona. In some places they are the same road. The scenery is beautiful. Gorgeous vintage buildings line the route in different little towns as you pass with long stretches of road in between. The rock formations on either side of the road make you feel as if you are in a movie. We took Route 66 all the way to Santa Monica Pier that year. Since we have had the pleasure to revisit some of the stretches of road again. We have been on stretches in Missouri and Illinois also. We want to be able to say we have taken it from beginning to end one day. There are so many memories I have made on this road that I could share. I hope to make many more in the future.

Name: Palmer Hotel
Narrative: I was fortunate to explore Afton when I did before a fire destroyed this building. There was just enough lighting for me to take this picture of the old motel.

Name: Route 66 Gasconade Bridge
Narrative: Seeing this bridge was a must when I drove through Missouri for the first time in 2018. Roamin' Rich's chair was still there that day and I did sit on it to show my support. Walking across this bridge was like walking on history. You never know what you got until it's gone, which thankfully is not the case for this bridge yet. I hear it's still standing today.

Name: Carlinville Wayside Exhibit
Narrative: I can't remember how this photo was taken. I may have had a friend with me. But I remember taking this photo and uploading it onto my Instagram and tagged the Illinois Route 66 Scenic Byway association in the post. It was picked as one of the photos in a voting contest for one month and my photo ended up being the winner! I won a Route 66  road sign, an Illinois Route 66 Scenic Byway cap, and an Illinois Route 66 license plate. And I absolutely love traveling through Carlinville.

Name: Glenrio, NM
Narrative: One of the coolest adventures I ever had on Route 66 was driving this dirt road from the city of Tucumcari, NM all the way to the ghost town Glenrio on the Texas border. The lighter side is New Mexico and the darker, Texas. Exploring the ghost town itself was awe-inspiring! And of course, Jeeps are photogenic, especially on dirt roads.

Name: Cross of our Lord Jesus Christ Ministries
Narrative: A place to rest. A place to stretch. A place to walk. A place to learn. A place to pray. A place to give. A place to love. A place to hope. A place to celebrate. A place to enjoy. A place for me. A place for you. A place for peace. A place for joy. A place for hope. A place to say, amen.

Name: John’s Modern Cabins
Narrative: Obscured by a canopy of trees, six tiny, crumbling cabins sit next to a quiet, dead-end stretch of Route 66 that runs parallel to Interstate 44 about 10 miles outside of Rolla, Mo.

Name: Lile Art Gallery
Narrative: Route 66 Destination

Name: Stinky's on Foothill Blvd.
Narrative: Stinky's was our favorite late-night hangout in high school and college. Renowned for the best greasy burgers and chili con carne. It was located at the corner of a lemon grove and made of stone. And, everyone carved their names in the tops of the wood picnic tables. It was unique!

Name: Gearhead Curios
Narrative: Gearhead Curios is a 1939 Texaco station that was built from native stone.  The old station was on Route 66 until June 1st 1963 when a new alignment put the station one block off of Route 66.  This station serviced travelers up through the 1980s.  A series of odd things for the next 10ish years, then it sat as storage for the next 15 or so years.  In Oct 2018 the old building was purchased by the Perry family & became Gearhead Curios, renovations began.  As renovation continued it became more of a travel destination.  An American Flag made from 169 Kansas license plates known as the Tag Flag greeted travelers in May 2020, the addition of a 1951 Hudson, a tribute to the character Doc joined Gearhead Curios in Aug 2020.  Vintage pumps & neon were installed in 2021.  In 2022 Gearhead Curios opened full time while renovations were still being competed.  June 2023 saw the official ribbon cutting.  The inside is full of unique memories & boasts the most photographed restroom on Route 66.

Name: Dwight, IL
Narrative: Getting Your Kicks on Route 66! How do two college BFFs celebrate a milestone birthday well.... In honor of celebrating our sixty sixth birthdays we jokingly said we should drive Route 66. And as usual we don't always do things in the most conventual way, we decided to drive the entirety of the original Route 66-in reverse. Most people depart Chicago and travel to California. We took a one-way flight to Los Angeles, rented a car, and drove east to Chicago ending our adventure back home in Kentucky. The road is straight and narrow and poorly identified in some areas. Trains speed across the desert next to highways and Route 66 meanders back and forth across both the highways and the train tracks. While an occasional U-turn, a dead end, or winding up in a few fields occurred, we had little or no traffic, no semi-trucks, and no impediments to a lovely drive. The weather was perfect (late May and early June 2023).
Narrative_Src: Share Your Story: Linda McNay & Kitty Dougoud

Name: Cactus Rose Taphouse
Narrative: I grew up a few blocks away from Route 66 in Britton, Ok. I went out into this great big world in the Summer of 1985. I have lived in several different places in this wonderful country of ours. Four and a half years ago I stumbled on an ad for a motel that was for sale in McLean, Tx. When I looked further it was right on Route 66. I decided at that moment that I wanted to buy it. It took everything I had to make it happen. With help from unexpected places, I purchased the CACTUS INN in McLean Texas on February 13th, 2020. Then Covid hits! By the grace of God I made it through. I have themed each of the rooms for the 8 states the Route travels. Texas has two rooms and I have a gallery room with art from my home. I moved to McLean in January 2022 and live here in the living quarters of the motel. I opened up the CACTUS ROSE TAPHOUSE on Main Street February 13 2022. It has been a crazy four years but both businesses are open!!!! Life comes full circle!

Name: Milburn-Price Culture Museum
Narrative: The Milburn-Price Culture Museum is a non-profit museum that seeks to educate the public about the western heritage and Route 66. With a Free Admission the museum is a great interactive place for all ages. The museum is housed in two buildings built in 1926 and 1928 along Route 66 and were originally Lumber and Hardware businesses. There are many things to see and do inside the museum buildings as well as outdoor exhibits and art pieces. Many of our Route 66 travelers comment that "this museum is the best stop on our trip so far" Located in the Texas Panhandle the museum is near the midpoint of Route 66 in Oldham County. Our slogan here is "When you're here, you're halfway there"

Name: Oklahoma Route 66 Museum
Narrative: We took a trip from San Bernardino to Albuquerque in our 1972 Olds 442 convertible the middle of the pandemic, because we wanted to go somewhere! Later we flew to ALBQQ, rented a Camaro SS convertible, and drove to Chicago, also during COVID. This photo was from Clinton, Oklahoma, where there was a Route 66 museum. We were one of two people in the place, as I'm sure hardly anyone was travelling at that time. We saw a LOT of points of interest, stayed at Grand Canyon Caverns Motel, El Rancho Hotel, Blue Swallow Motel, Boots Motel and Wagon Wheel Motel. we saw, ate, and experienced as many Route 66 attractions as we could! They were great trips.

Name: Mojave Desert
Narrative: I traveled the entirety of Route 66 as an undergrad in 2004 en route from my home in Ohio to Chicago to LA. The trip changed the trajectory of my life, cementing a passion for roadside architecture and providing the underpinnings of a career in a field I wouldn't properly discover existed for another few years - historic preservation. I've since gotten a Master's degree in preservation (where I did a thesis on neon sign preservation), run a preservation advocacy organization in a major American city, and served on the board of a national roadside architecture preservation organization. And it really started with this trip. Every stop was as intriguing as the next, but the most surprising was California's Mojave Desert, that vast expanse that too many miss because they drive through at night or are told there's nothing there. To the contrary, these stalwart businesses and the evocative landscape surrounding them stir the soul like nowhere else. See it in the daylight!

Name: Goffs, CA
Narrative: Goffs, CA, is a historic town located in the Mojave Desert, about two hours east of Barstow, CA. It used to be a stop on Route 66 until Route 66 was diverted in the 1930's and then it was used as a training base for artillery troops. Today, Goff's is a stopping point for the offroaders on the Mojave road, and it houses two working stamp mills, a restored school house, museum collection and archives, a blacksmith area, and many other artifacts and historic buildings that have been donated by homesteaders, railroaders and miners over the years. They even have an annual camel run.

Name: Illinois Route 66 Experience at Illinois State Fairground
Narrative: The Route 66 Experience Is an outdoor educational exhibit open 365 days a year offering a self-guided experience highlighting businesses from 90+ Illinois communities located along Route 66.   Beginning in Chicago and ending at the Chain of Rocks Bridge near St. Louis, this attraction has vintage billboards, a drive in movie theater, the Legends Neon Sign Park, as well as a tribute to the muffler men located along Illinois famous mother road. The desire to educate youth, bring back the road trip, and promote Illinois 66 communities was the driving force behind this project. To visit enter the main gate of the Illinois State Fairgrounds and take the first two right turns.

Name: Bearizona Wildlife Park
Narrative: My wife and I decided our honeymoon would be a cross-country road trip, from our home in New York to California and back. We knew we wanted to spend some time driving down historic Route 66, and we shared as such while on a wine tour in Sonoma, CA. Someone on the tour mentioned we should check out a place called Bearizona, a wildlife preserve right on Route 66. We completely forgot the suggestion until we were driving through Williams, Arizona and drove right by the entrance! We immediately pulled over and spent the afternoon marveling as we drove past bears, wolves, bison, big horn sheep, and more.

Name: Madonna of the Trail
Narrative: I was born 75 years ago in Upland CA and the Madonna on the Trail at the intersection of Route 66 and Euclid Avenue was a frequent centerpiece for holiday and other photos.

Name: Pink Elephant Antique Mall
Narrative: The Pink Elephant Antique Mall in the old Livingston IL High School built in 1927.  Several fiberglass giants (muffler man, beach guy, pink elephant, Futuro UFO home, greet travelers on Route 66, 1950s themed Twistee Treat Diner, a vintage candy and fudge shop, Route 66 souvenirs.  A must stop along Route 66 in Illinois.

Name: Southwest Boulevard bridge
Narrative: When Cyrus Avery suggested that US Highway 66 dip down through Oklahoma on its way from Chicago to Los Angeles, he leveraged Tulsa's state-of-the-art 11th Street Bridge as the safest crossing over the Arkansas River. Because of his advocacy, Avery's adopted home town became a key spot along the famous highway. Because of this heritage, the city today calls itself the Capital of Route 66.

Name: Bernies Bar & Grill
Narrative: We stopped at Bernie's when we traveled cross country and it was the highlight of the trip! The bartenders were so kind and told us all about living in the small-town Avilla. It was everything we thought a Route 66 business would be like...and more. I will ALWAYS cherish this memory of of driving through this tiny main street and stopping in for a cold beer. It was a true American experience.
Narrative_Src: Share Your Story: Brittany Lavelle Tulla

Name: Bourbon Café and Coffee Saloon
Narrative: During our west to east traverse of Rt 66 during June and July of 2023, we ran across this wonderful spot in Bourbon, MO.  The place was freshly restored and we were entertained by a group of retiree musicians and enjoyed excellent food.  When we left, staff and patrons came out to send us on our way down 66.  This type of small town hospitality was a highlight of our trip.

Name: Route 66 Auto Museum
Narrative: So many cool museums along route 66 with beautiful antique cars and trucks.

Name: Mother Jones Monument
Narrative: The grave of Mother Jone's, in Mount Olive. Illinois, in the Miners' Cemetery, is, as I recall, right along the original route of the "mother road". But I don't remember ever seeing it mentioned in any of the interpretive celebrations of Route 66. Even Gene Autry recorded a song in her memory (1931), and the modern magazine has kept her name alive. We took this focused picture on a gray day in the summer of 2016, when we stopped to honor her memory en route through Chicago to our home in Southern California- most of the way on 66. Sure, we enjoyed the blue whale, and the other kitschy or commercial landmarks, but this monument to labor, and this champion of labor Mother Jones, was one of the most moving. The site deserves to be better recognized, alongside of  the quirky sites which line this route that are more celebrated, if more superficial.

Name: Route 66 California
Narrative: In the summer of 1992, I traveled cross-country for four months, visiting all 48 contiguous states. The highlight of the trip was my journey along the entire length of Route 66, from Lake Michigan to the Pacific Ocean. The entire trip was life-changing, but motoring along the Mother Road, from end to end, was the highlight. I no longer have most of my pictures from that trip, but here's one I took not long after crossing from Arizona into California.

Name: Devils Elbow Bridge
Narrative: The narrow highway bridge at Devil's Elbow is a must. You don't find too many bridges like this National Register beauty.

Name: Sacred Heart Church
Narrative: On the Santa Fe Loop of Route 66 lies the tiny village of Dilia, NM.  Inhabited over 10,000 years, the area was visited by the explorer Coronado in 1540. Situated on the Pecos River, it was witness to the Long Walk of the Navajo in 1864 to the Bosque Redondo at Ft.Sumner, NM.  The Sacred Heart Church (pictured) was built in 1900.

Name: California Route 66 Museum
Narrative: Loved the Route 66 Museum at Victorville, CA

Name: California Route 66 Museum Water Damage Preservation and Prevention
Route History
Narrative: Route History Museum is the only brick and mortar museum in the United States that highlights the significance of the Black experience along Historic Route 66 using technology. Route History Museum fully integrates history and technology through exhibits, storytelling, and a virtual reality experience that highlights the significant roles of Black businesses, the Negro Motorist Green Book, the Great Migration, and sundown towns along the Illinois leg of Route 66 during the Civil Rights and Jim Crow eras.

Name: Guardian Lions of Route 66
Narrative: Route 66 is full of hidden treasures and mysteries that fill peoples imagination. One of the mysteries is the set of guardian lions found in the desert of Amboy California. Surrounded by nothing but sand and clouds these majestic marble statues stand over 6 feet tall and rest on concrete cinder blocks. No one really knows how they got here but what I love them is that everyone has attached their own meaning to them, Some people make them into make shift memorial while others see them as a sign of good luck. Pictured here is the female statue, the male statue is about a quarter mile down the road.

Name: Chicago, IL
Narrative: One of the things I love most about journeying down Route 66 is the appreciation it gives you for America's beautiful landscapes. I started in Chicago, and in the weeks I spent on the road, I experienced expansive plains, mesmerizing cornfields, raging rivers, deserts, mountains, and finally the beautiful Pacific coast. With each changing view, I could not help but think that diversity makes our country so unique. Always keep your eye on the road and your camera at hand ? you'll be surprised at every turn (and there are many).

Name: Slaughter Building
Narrative: During segregation, the Randolph Family Drug Store in Oklahoma City's Deep Deuce was a vital stop for Black travelers along Route 66. Listed in the Negro Motorist Green Book, Randolph Drug offered soda fountain refreshments, light lunches, a place to gather and everyday essentials. Operated by the Randolph family, the store was housed in the Slaughter Building, owned by Dr. W.H. Slaughter, their son-in-law, and a key figure in the community. Most of the historic Black sites from that era are demolished, Dr. Slaughter's and wife Edna Randoph-Slaughter's former home remains standing. Now known as The Mansion, it has been restored by Doris and Marq Youngblood as a short-term rental and a place to gather. The home stands to preserve the enduring legacy of African Americans who found refuge with the Slaughters and Randolphs at Randoph Drug. Photo Credit: Courtesy of the Oklahoma Historical Society
Narrative_Src: Share Your Story: Doris & Marquett Youngblood
Image_Cr: Courtesy of the Oklahoma Historical Society

Narrative: During segregation, the Randolph Family Drug Store in Oklahoma City's Deep Deuce was a vital stop for Black travelers along Route 66.
