Name: Route 66 New Mexico
Narrative: US Highway 66 saw many improvements throughout its life, including the addition of more lanes in places like Santa Rosa.

Name: Santa Monica Pier
Narrative: As a way to experience the Mother Road and promote my 2010 exhibition "Route 66: The Road and the Romance" at the Autry Museum, we drove the entire route from Michigan Ave to the Santa Monica Pier with this invitation on the side of the car urging people to "Follow us!" Now, ten years later, a second exhibit inspired by artists of the highway, "Eyes on the Road" is about to open in April at the Petersen Automotive Museum in Los Angeles. See the oldest Route 66 shield displayed with Ed Ruscha's "Rusty Signs" and a lot more!

Name: Alleyway Mural
Narrative: An alleyway mural in Vinita, Oklahoma ties Route 66 into many aspects of local culture and pride. Vinita is one of the first towns settled in the region.

Name: Farmrail Train
Narrative: Another example of American industry seen along Route 66.
Narrative_Src: Share Your Story: R. Dean Larson

Name: Historic Route 66 Gas Station
Narrative: Near Arcadia, OK, the hundred year old ruins of an old gas station beckon Route 66 travelers to explore and enjoy. The stone structure still stands, and local caretakers fly the Stars and Stripes proudly saying, yes, this is Our America.

Name: Snell Road
Narrative: Original brick Route 66 near Auburn Illinois and our C-7

Name: Hext, OK
Narrative: Just north of the current roadway between Sayre and Erick, OK, visible in some places and obscured by trees and overgrowth in others, lies two lanes of a 1929 alignment. For many years, these two lanes carried motorists until the arrival of the interstate in 1975, which left this original stretch of road abandoned, the last segment of Route 66 in Oklahoma to lose its U.S. Highway designation. Despite being just shy of its 100th birthday, stretches of original Portland Cement concrete peek through later-added layers of asphalt that have worn away.An experience that was so moving it had us struggling to put our feelings into words; this was one of those moments that made time stand still and, maybe, almost, for a moment, made us believe that time travel was possible and we had actually stepped back in time.

Name: South Michigan Ave
Narrative: Started this road trip, by motorcycle, on July 21, 2024, from Chicago, celebrating my 66th anniversary. It was great seeing how much the City had changed in the last 40 years (I used to live there in 1974).

Name: T-rex statue
Narrative: Between 2013-2018, I'd travel to Heber-Overgaard, AZ to see family who lived there and had to pass through Holbrook, AZ from I-40/Rte 66.  One time, I took a few minutes to actually look at Holbrook on Rte 66 beyond the way through when I spied this T-Rex trying to scare people.  It didn't scare me away from taking its portrait, so it posed for me and this is what I have of that memory.  I love traveling the Mother Road when I get a chance to, among all of the other original US Highways.  Fond memories abound!

We are Team Rammar. We hope to Hike, Bike, Swim, visit the Capital, and Ice Sk8 in all 50 States. While enroute to hike the Grand Canyon South Rim, we pulled off I-40 to sleep in a field. The next morning we saw a little town with a gas station in the distance.  Without knowing it, we pulled into this store?s lot to park our 29ft. Fleetwood Tioga RV and went inside. We bought a bottle of hot sauce to go and documented where we were with video of the road and a fellow Route 66 traveler, a  live walking taranchula. Arizona bypass was the location just before the Williams Junction to the Grand Canyon South Rim. Arizona was our 13th State to visit. We able to hike/bike the Grand Canyon, then Ice Skate at the Ice Den in Pheonix, and Ice Skate with my son at Az Ice in Gilbert where he was attending the ATP Flight Training Program and celebrate his Birthday at Applebees. We are now in Alabama, our 19th State to visit and Sk8. We are still on the road traveling, and visit route 66 again soon!!
Narrative_Src: Share Your Story: Richard Marks and Margie Fano

Name: Hunt's Trailer Park
Narrative: Kristen and I are avid fans of Route 66.  It began with a family road trip west along the Route after watching Disney's Cars.  We stayed at the Blue Swallow and immediately fell in love with the people we met along the route.  Fast forward to 2022 and we were able to purchase our own piece of Route 66 with the hopes of reopening Hunt's as a retro RV park.

Name: Gallup Amtrack Station
Narrative: I was in the 2nd grade when all of a sudden our teacher, Ms. Parker walked hurriedly into the classroom.      She got all of us in a line and marched us to the playground where we waited for the balance of students to come to the playground.       We were marched in single file to theTrain Station on Route 66 with out being told the reason for this adventure.    When we got there, we saw thousands of people had gathered. I had a good view of the ceremony    Then, a train came to the station with a caboose  Every body started to clap and cheer wildly. I found out the reason for all the excitement.  Hiroshi  ?Hershey ? Miyamura was awarded the Congressional Medal of Honor by President Eisenhower in Washington DC. for his heroic actions in the Korean War.          From my position in the crowd I could see Mr Miyamura in his military uniform.

Name: The Last California Information Bureau Office Left
Narrative: Built by the California Information Bureau in the 1920s, these small buildings could be found at several Agricultural Inspection Stations across California. The last remaining one is along Route 66 in Daggett, California. Operating in cooperation with the California Board of Trade, the California Information Bureau offices were the original Welcome Centers for California and served the same function as our modern California Welcome Centers currently operated by California Office of Tourism. The Daggett building was sold in 1930 about the time when the original Agricultural Inspection Station in Daggett was moved. The building served as a private residence until recently. It now is a being restored to its original appearance and will serve as a museum.

Name: Bus stop
Narrative: Took this on our journey through New Mexico -- a bus stop at dusk. Oct ?23

Name: Alf's Blacksmith Shop
Narrative: Alf's Blacksmith Shop was built and owned by my great great grandfather, Seymore Alf, in 1890. It is located in Daggett, CA, along Route 66 east of Barstow. Some of the famous 20 Mule Team wagons that hauled borax out of the desert were built at and operated from the shop. Later, Seymore went into road building and used his mule teams and scrapers to grade long sections of Route 66 through the Mojave, particularly the segment from Barstow to Needles. A 1911 newspaper article called him the "pioneer road master of the desert country.? His blacksmith shop still stands and is preserved almost exactly as it was in the 1890s; tools, forge, and all. It is a California Point of Historical Interest and I am currently working with the Daggett & Calico Historical Society to nominate it to the National Register of Historic Places!

Name: Pleasantdale School District on Route 66
Narrative: Historical Ties to Route 66: A Journey Through Pleasantdale School District 107Join us on a journey back in time to explore the rich history of Pleasantdale School District 107 and its connection to the iconic Route 66. Step into our log cabin, which served as the district's humble beginnings in 1843, nestled on the corner of Wolf Road and Joliet Road. While our district has relocated over the years, our current school building remains just a stone's throw away from this historic route. As you venture to the corner where it all started, you'll notice the Lyonsville Church. On this very corner, an enduring rock stands, commemorating our school's remarkable heritage and longstanding ties to Joliet Road. Come and discover the fascinating story of Pleasantdale School District 107, intricately intertwined with the local Route 66, a symbol of American history and culture.

Name: Ozarks Country Store
Narrative: Pictured is the McMenus General Store in what is believed to be the first image of RT-66 in Phillipsburg MO. It is more commonly known as the General Store and is currently undergoing a renovation which will include a full renovation and an electric vehicle charging park adjacent to the west. I have some amazing history of the building as the center of town going back to 1900 when it was first built. The original theater is still upstairs with 100+ years of milestones and notes still appearing on the original plaster walls intact with the original, chairs, backdrop and more. I would be very interested in giving a tours, narrating a submission and or providing a more extensive history as needed. This was on the first inception of the route I am told with a bypass circumventing this location in the early 1930s. The route moved about a quarter mile to a newer paved road slightly to the west where another McMenus business opened

Name: The Copper State Court
Narrative: My great-aunt and uncle, Zelma and Ezell Nelson, owned the Copper State Court in Ash Fork, Arizona, for over 40 years. Zelma was a Harvey Girl at the Harvey House in Kingman; Ezell a cowboy from New Mexico working in the kitchen. They opened a restaurant in Peach Springs before building the Copper State's cabins from flagstone in the 1930s. My grandmother spent WWII there while my grandfather was overseas. My father, a Prescott native, spent summers there in the 1950s and 60s. When my uncle died in the 1970s, not long after I-40 bypassed the town, my aunt moved to Phoenix. Yet their story remains along the mother road to this day.

Name: Smith's
Narrative: It is not there now and when I was young it had seen better times but you could tell that in its prime it was one of the stars of ALB.  For what ever reason one summer in the early seventies we did not have a vacation destination.  it could have been plans feel through or maybe a lack of funds.  A family of 11 total ended up at the Western skies for a week even though we were natives to the city.  At prior times this would never have been able to occur but the hotel needed the money and and we needed the summer diversion.  You could tell that the once state of the art accommodations and decor had seen better times, but we loved it.  The pool was large and we had the run of the place, except of course the suite that JFK had stayed.  There was a plaque outside the door and we would always lower our voices if we passed by, almost like a church.  Of course it was located on RT 66 as anything of importance of and for me represents my definition of the iconic highway
